\par\par \b \uc2 A new 'religion' for urbanites: shopping\b0\par\par\uc2 818 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 August 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 22\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Carla Bianpoen, Contributor, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Going on a shopping spree for many signifies leisure, fun, and has become an inseparable part of contemporary urban life.\par \par \uc2 Pentagram, a digital print on acrylic by Ade Darmawani.\par \par \uc2 Why is shopping so (fatally) attractive to urbanites -- and non-urbanites? Does it make people feel like they are attaining lost or unreachable dreams?\par \par \uc2 Whatever the reason, shopping as an expression of increased \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  welfare, and in many ways of social standing, has evolved from a mere activity of purchasing basic foods in the market place, to one that reflects multiple issues related to consumerism and psychological disturbances or dysfunctions.\par \par \uc2 This is made evident in Shopping, an exhibition curated by Rifky Effendy and organized by Nadi Gallery at the Jakarta Art District of the Grand Indonesia mall.\par \par \uc2 Right from the entrance of the Jakarta Art District's communal space where the show is currently held, engraved text on a large bag brings forward the complex issues that underlie the term "shopping".\par \par \uc2 While shopping often morphs into an addiction, with people feeling an almost uncontrollable desire to shop, the activity may also compensate for feelings of grief, greed, anger and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The act of shopping can also indicate a search for healing, clarity, growth or the intent to move on after life problems.\par \par \uc2 Astari's iconic bag, initially covered with words like Greed, \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Fear, Anger and the like, now features the terms Denial, Acceptance and Awareness, hinting at the artist's personal experiences. As such, the shopping bag, titled Shopping for Recovery, has become an important medium of expression for the artist.\par \par \uc2 The roses and the Wayang Tree of Life tucked into the bag convey a sense of shopping's deeper meaning in the artist's life.\par \par \uc2 Of a different kind, but still carrying a similar message, Theresia Agustina Sitompul's installation -- a shop window displaying a white dress with a multitude of sleeves accompanied by the constant ticking sound of a sewing machine -- refers to an industry that perpetually challenges a woman's desire for fashion and beauty. It is aptly titled All In the Name of Desire.\par \par \uc2 In fact, urban life is steeped in an overflow of tantalizing products evoking the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's desire to buy beyond their basic needs. Ade Darmawan's Pentagram reveals the powers out to challenge man's abilities to think rationally. The artist uses an image of hands reaching out to a human brain inside a shopping trolley to convey the magic of consumerism.\par \par \uc2 But this magic may not be obvious to those busy running errands in suburban shops where everything but luxurious goods is available, as is presented in Anggun Priambodo's Toko Keperluan, a shop selling basic commodities like eggs -- although a TV is also for sale.\par \par \uc2 All in the Name of Desire, installation made of fabric, steel and an electronic player, by Theresia Agustina.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps the most ingenious work in the exhibition is Dipo Andy's Canting Project, which presents a range of old canting, a device used to make batik. While there has been much talk recently about batik representing national identity, the little canting, the oldest tool in civilization, is often forgotten, says the artist.\par \par \uc2 Yet this small device enables the batik maker to infuse his work of art with a touch of his soul, giving the batik cloth its genuine features sought by batik connoisseurs.\par \par \uc2 The exhibition presents the concept of shopping from many angles, from the shop where every day products are available, to mere boxes, like Arief Tousiga's soap box mimicking Andy Warhol's Brillo soap box, or Ketut Moniarta's Pocari Sweat Box that reminds patients afflicted by dengue fever of the healing liquid they had to swallow to recover.\par \par \uc2 In the world of shopping, certain brands like Louis Vuitton, Chanel, or Prada conjure images of the rich, fashionable and beautiful. Nadia Savitri's work titled All I Ever Wanted, consisting of ceramic mechanic tools engraved with the word Chanel, is a sarcastic take on such a perception. Another neon light box, made by Angki Purbandono, depicts children's toys, an exciting practice that he has entertained the masses immensely lately.\par \par \uc2 Shopping indeed can be fun, as we indulge in fantasies and dreams, and the greater fun of this is of course that fantasies don't have to end, and neither do dreams, for one can go on shopping until the end of time. But the dream must surely stop as banknotes lose their value. Adya Ranadireksa's seems to suggest so, in his work depicting fading images of national heroes on banknotes.\par \par \uc2 The exhibition, which also includes works by Abdi Setiawan, Agan Harahap, Davy linggar, Indra Ameng, and many more, fits amazingly well in the shopping mall of Grand Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 -- Photos by Carla Bianpoen\par \par \uc2 Shopping\par \par \uc2 Exhibition by Nadi Gallery\par \par \uc2 Until Aug. 16\par \par \uc2 Jakarta Art District\par \par \uc2 Grand Indonesian East Mall, LG.\par \par \uc2 Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020100825e68c0019r\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Land Prices in Indonesia Considered the Cheapest; Business Climate  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2  Threatens New Property Projects\b0\par\par\uc2 660 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 August 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia    \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The average price of property areas in Indonesia is the cheapest compared to those in 11 Asian countries. The average price is US$1,381 per square meter. In the meantime, the average land price in Hong Kong is the highest at US$16,422 per square meter.\par \par \uc2 Information by Global Property Guide as of the second quarter of 2010 showed the average land price in Indonesia was far lower than the land prices in Cambodia, the Philippines, and Malaysia.\par \par \uc2 The average property area price is calculated based on the research of housing area prices collected from ad bureaus and marketing offices. Some indicators used are new building sales, leasing fee, and resale value.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, property areas referred to here are areas used for apartment, condominium, industrial area, office building, and business center that boasts apartment.\par \par \uc2 Based on the data, the average land price in Malaysia was 3.11% more expensive than Indonesia at US$1,424 per square meter, while the average land prices in the Philippine and Cambodia were 47.21% and 93.19% more expensive, respectively, than Indonesia at US$2,033 and US$2,668 per square meter, respectively.\par \par \uc2 Such a condition in Indonesia was in line with data exposed by Cushman & Wakefield Indonesia (CWI), which exposed that the average condominium area price in Jakarta hovered at IDR4.5 million (US$500) per square meter to IDR18.8 million (US$2.089) per square meter.\par \par \uc2 Compared to Singapore, the average land price in Indonesia was cheaper by a whopping 720% since the average land price in Singapore is US$11,324 per square meter. In China and Singapore, the average land prices are US$5,449 per square meter and US$12,884 per square meter, respectively.\par \par \uc2 Despite the comparatively low price, the analysis added, the property area prices in Indonesia were highly prospective since most of the buildings had sufficient facilities and maintenance support over the past five years.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the monthly outlook was potential to steadily increase in terms of apartment, condo, and strata title projects. Moreover, the occupancy rate was estimated to increase in the third quarter of 2010.\par \par \uc2 Moderate rating\par \par \uc2 The analysis also spotlighted the competitiveness of Indonesian property business against 26 countries in Asia. The indicators were macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, government policies, and technological readiness.\par \par \uc2 Based on the indicators, Indonesia was only ranked 11th, with a competitiveness index reaching 4.26 or hovering at a moderate level. In the meantime, the worst competitiveness went to Timor Leste, which recorded an index of 3.26.\par \par \uc2 The highest competitiveness index of 5.55 was posted by Singapore. The small country, which once was battered by the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, was able to outstrip property giant Japan (5.37), Hong Kong (5.22), Taiwan (5,2) and South Korea (5.0) at the end of the first semester of 2010.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Central Leaders' Board of the Indonesian National Contractors Association (BPP-Gapensi) Soeharsojo disclosed the competitiveness of Indonesian property industry was potential to keep declining if the government didn't issue three basic policies to bolster competitiveness: land regulations that favored developers, simpler licensing process, and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  holidays.\par \par \uc2 "The land acquisition process is always problematic. There are also multiple property \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed on us. Without business certainty, new property projects will be curbed," he told Bisnis yesterday.\par \par \uc2 In terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he added, local as well as foreign investors were still charged with various levies, such as BPHTB (fee for rights over building and land), sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on luxurious goods (PPnBM), and VATs of 5%, 21%, and 10% of property prices.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, gross rental yield per annum in the Indonesian property sector in the long term was actually very promising. In Asia, the yield of property investment in Indonesia is ranked highest at 11.38%. (Bisnis/yuw)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020100813e68d00009\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 'Govt Too Pessimistic'; Commitment and Promises to Procure Infrastructures Stalled\b0\par\par\uc2 1,097 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 August 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Some parties view that the government is too pessimistic toward Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by setting lower macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators from what they should be.\par \par \uc2 Dradjad Hari Wibowo, an economist at Sustainable Development Indonesia, revealed Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2011 could be bolstered higher to reach at least 6.7%-7.1%. To meet the target, the real problems that the government had to pay attention to were the problems of energy supply and rupiah overvaluation.\par \par \uc2 "If energy supply is insufficient, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth can be dragged down to around 6%. Another problem is the rupiah overvaluation has disturbed export and regional infrastructures," he said yesterday when asked for his comment and criticism on the President's speech ahead Independence Day on August 17.\par \par \uc2 According to Dradjad, there were some external factors that the government had to stay alert for in maintaining \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth momentum. The first factor was the potential surge in global food and commodity prices on fire in Russia and climate \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The second factor was the fact that the global confidence had not yet fully recovered on \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the banking sector recovery in the US.\par \par \uc2 "However, the surging price can be reversed to trigger growth if Indonesia is able to bolster food production, such as sugar, milk, meat, and horticultural production. So, the food sector next year is potential to trigger growth."\par \par \uc2 An economist at the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) Ahmad Erani Yustika argued \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year could reach 6.7% since \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in Asia was on the good track. Therefore, the government had to be able to accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth by empowering the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  potential and accelerating \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  absorption.\par \par \uc2 "If the government only targets \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth at 6.2%-6.5% for 2011, it means that the government won't be willing to work hard."\par \par \uc2 Acting Head of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency Agus Supriyanto disclosed the government still stuck to macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumptions in the 2011 Revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which had been submitted to the House.\par \par \uc2 The assumptions fix \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth at 6.1%-6.4%, the rupiah exchange rate to the US dollar at IDR9,100-IDR9,400, inflation at 4.9%-5.3%, interest rate at 6.2%-6.5%, Indonesia Crude Price (ICP) at US$75-US$90 per barrel, and oil lifting at 960,000-967,000 barrels per day.\par \par \uc2 Minister of Finance Agus D.W. Martowardojo confirmed the government had already had absolute figures for all macroeconomic indicators for 2011. The absolute figures would serve as the basis for the 2011 Revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft that President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono would introduce.\par \par \uc2 Sunarsip, Chief Economist at The Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Intelligence (IEI), viewed the government lacked optimism in setting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target for next year. According to him, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for 2011 might reach 6.5%.\par \par \uc2 As for inflation, he viewed the government was too optimistic by fixing inflation at 4.9%-5.3%, leading three-month SBI interest rate to be fixed lower at 6.2%-6.5%. Ideally, he added, inflation was set at 5.5%-6.5%, while three-month SBI interest rate was fixed higher than the initial projection.\par \par \uc2 Sunarsip disclosed macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability was relatively maintained well. The government instead should focus on micro-sectors, such as the agricultural and manufacturing sectors, which became the largest contributors to GDP.\par \par \uc2 "The growths [of the manufacturing and agricultural sectors] have been lower than the average national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth over the past few years. There are micro structural problems that have to be addressed in the two sectors."\par \par \uc2 An economist at the Center for Information and Development Studies (Cides) Umar Juoro thought that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth could grow by more than 6.4% if investment climate was improved and supported by infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 Infrastructure development\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the business industry hopes the government can help provide funds to infrastructure development to accelerate the real sector in the 2011 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a form of concrete support from the government to accelerate the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) Sofjan Wanandi disclosed the real sector so far had not received full commitment and attention from the government, leading the sector to move slowly.\par \par \uc2 To support the real sector, he continued, the industries needed the government's full commitment to procure infrastructures, such as electricity, road, port, and cheap primary energies, such as gas. So far, the realization of the commitment had been stalled.\par \par \uc2 "We hope the President can be committed to developing infrastructures, which currently are stalled. How can we expect the real sector to move? The President should no longer talk about monetary situation anymore since our monetary conditions have been well-maintained and controllable."\par \par \uc2 At least, added Sofjan, the President could again put an emphasis on the problem of legal certainty and make sure that the delegation of his authority to his ministers to develop infrastructures could run effectively.\par \par \uc2 The concrete form of this would be seen from the amount of \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocated to infrastructure procurement in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which will be read by the President. "The President has to spend more on development. All this time, 90% of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has gone to routine expenditures and debt payment."\par \par \uc2 The national transportation operators view the performance of the transportation infrastructure sector was still declining, lowering competitiveness. They viewed the connection between international and national networks as urgent and this would require cross-ministerial and G-to-G policies.\par \par \uc2 "The sector covers infrastructure, financing, and law enforcement, which require strong \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  directives and clear message to the business industry," explained Carmelita Hartoto, Chairperson of the Sea Transportation Permanent Committee at the Indonesian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (Kadin).\par \par \uc2 Serious attention, Carmelia said, should be focused on dealing with problems in the national transportation sector, such as poor road infrastructure, declining port competitiveness, and high logistical cost.\par \par \uc2 Johnson W. Sutjipto, Chairperson of the Indonesian National Shipowners' Association (INSA), said port infrastructures had to be improved to support the growth of the national sea transportation sector.\par \par \uc2 Ports in Indonesia had to be improved to end the domination of Singapore and Malaysia.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Indonesia Transportation Society (MTI) Danang Parikesit argued goods and service mobility in the land, sea, and air transportations over the past five years had been growing significantly.\par \par \uc2 "The increased goods and service mobility in Indonesia over the past five years should become a missed opportunity to make the national businesses the winners in their own turf." (Bisnis/agi/aca/aji/raf/smu)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020100816e68g0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
