\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Domestic bond market: Go with the flow\b0\par\par\uc2 594 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 August 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Andry Asmoro, Bahana Securities,\par \par \uc2 How Indonesia's bond market has rapidly recovered since last year's big correction on the back of global financial crisis. In fact, in 2010, the Indonesia bond market has provided one of the highest returns in the region on the back of relatively better yields and expected improved rating next year.\par \par \uc2 Point in case would be the approximate 12 percent capital gain if investors were to purchase 10-year bonds in the beginning of the year and sold it on Wednesday (Aug. 25, 2010). Coupled with 5 percent coupon for the first six months of this year, investors could earn in aggregate some 17 percent gain at present.\par \par \uc2 However, this phenomenon is not only limited to Indonesia. Over the same period, Thailand's 10-year government bond would also provide capital gain of around 11 percent. With global investors continuing to remain cautious on the recovery pace in advanced countries, the global bond markets have continued to benefit from fund flows. In the US, market participants expect that the Fed funds rate would remain at between 0 and 0.25 percent for an extended period.\par \par \uc2 Hence, we believe foreign capital will continue to seek higher yields. This is particularly applicable for the Indonesia bond market, which still offers better yield spreads (to US treasury notes) than other countries in the region such as Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the relatively stable rupiah (IDR) has also lowered currency risk. As of Wednesday, the IDR volatility is below 1.5 percent, suggesting a stable currency with shocks unlikely to materialize, supported by solid macroeconomic and political condition.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, the expectations are for Indonesia's rating to be upgraded to investment grade sometime in 2011. However, it could become a risk, if this upgrade does not materialize, resulting in disappointment for investors.\par \par \uc2 Other risks that could come about would be slower export and direct investments given the current global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A chart on the Baltic Dry Index, an indicator for commodity shipments, shows continued weakness, unable to return to its five-year average. Fortunately, Indonesia remains relatively well shielded against these external vagaries given domestic consumption accounts for more than 65 percent of total GDP.\par \par \uc2 Finally, we see the rising foreign ownership in governments bonds (please see chart for details) itself to also be a form risk which could result in severe volatility when funds flow out. This could be triggered by domestic inflationary pressure, for instance, which could result in rising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 We believe that August and September inflation rates would remain at elevated levels, coming in at around 1 percent for this month, bringing year-to-date inflation rate to around 5 percent. We expect this to rise to 6.3 percent by year-end. In 2011, much will hinge on the government's decision on price adjustments in LPG and electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  increases. At this stage, we expect next year's inflation to reach 6.5 percent, slightly higher than this year, in line with the pick up in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth as well as lofty commodity food prices stemming from capricious weather patterns.\par \par \uc2 We advise investors to remain vigilant, as the first sign of higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could result in souring sentiment for not only the bond market but also for the equity market. While the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  intends to keep rate unchanged, continued spikes in inflation could force \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to implement higher rates as early as 4Q10.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at PT Bahana Securities\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020100826e68q0005l\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Global Recovery Slowing Down; Indonesia's Export and Investment to be Strengthened to Deal with Global  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Impacts\b0\par\par\uc2 862 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 August 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Several central banks in developed countries start giving signals to launch additional stimuli in the wake of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery slowdown, while the government is asked to anticipate the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impacts.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Federal Reserve (The Fed) Ben S. Bernanke exposed the Federal Reserve had policies to prevent the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from falling into double-dip.\par \par \uc2 "We are ready to provide additional monetary stimuli through non-conventional policies if necessary, especially if the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook is bleak," he stated in his speech before the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials and economists from 40 countries at the Federal Reserve annual symposium in Jackson Hole, Kansas City, Wyoming, the US, as quoted by Bloomberg last weekend.\par \par \uc2 Bernanke made his speech only a few hours after the US announced its Q2 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance slowed down.\par \par \uc2 The US Department of Trade recorded the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew 1.6% (year-on-year), lower than 2.4% previously estimated.\par \par \uc2 From England, Bank of England Deputy Governor Charle