\par\par \b \uc2 Global  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  continuously shifting to Asian markets\b0\par\par\uc2 472 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 October 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post    \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia will benefit from an ongoing shift of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity towards emerging Asian markets, analyst says.\par \par \uc2 The new trend is a result of the recent global financial downturn affecting many Western countries, Deloitte Asia Pacific CEO Chaly Mah said.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in many Western countries affected by the global financial crisis is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It's relatively patchy," he told The Jakarta Post during a recent interview.\par \par \uc2 Many Western countries, including the US, are still suffering, he said.\par \par \uc2 "They are still struggling with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges, and the unemployment rate remains high. There is still no clear sign of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth there," Mah said on the sidelines of an investment seminar entitled "Exploring the investment outlook in Indonesia 2009-2014", held to celebrate the 20th anniversary of Deloitte Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity was now shifting to Asia because of its huge population, Mah said.\par \par \uc2 "Asia is a big \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  market for multinational companies. It will remain economically strong despite the global crisis," said Mah, citing China's population of 1.3 billion people, India's 1.1 billion and almost 600 million people in ASEAN, 240 million of which are Indonesian.\par \par \uc2 Even after the global crisis, Asia will still attract investments and continue to grow because everybody is looking at the region, he said.\par \par \uc2 However, many challenges confront emerging Asian economies, including Indonesia, while they compete to lure foreign investment.\par \par \uc2 Vietnam, for example, is seen as a promising location due to certain advantages, such as cheap labor, and China remains one of Asia's best investment destinations, Mah said.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, Indonesia had many similar strong points, including a healthy working class population, affordable labor costs and a strong macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as indicated by the country's hefty per capita GDP, which is expected to exceed US$3,600 by 2012, he said.\par \par \uc2 "A significant working class population is one of Indonesia's key strong points in attracting larger investments," Mah said, referring to 58 million working class Indonesians.\par \par \uc2 With its 1.3 billion people, it is difficult to make comparisons to China in terms of population, but China's major cities in the eastern coastal areas have shown significant increases in cost of living, Mah said.\par \par \uc2 The Chinese government was encouraging multinational companies to invest in the western part of the country, where infrastructure might not be as well-developed, he said.\par \par \uc2 Another Indonesian other advantage was its abundant natural resources, such as oil and natural gas \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Mah said.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's democratic political environment might also serve as another advantage.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia has been an open \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for many years, even before the 1998 Asian crisis. This is a strong point when compared to other emerging markets," Mah said, adding that government stability in Indonesia helped boost investor confidence. (ebf)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101002e6a200018\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Five Sector Indices Still Falter; Consumer and Industry Stock Rallies Highly Possible\b0\par\par\uc2 1,035 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 October 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Although the Composite Stock Index (IHSG) performance has far exceeded expectation, the performances of five of nine sector indices have not yet recovered to the pre-2008 global financial crisis level.\par \par \uc2 The five indices are the infrastructure, mining, property, trade, and agriculture indices. Analysts view that it will take time for the five indices to rebound.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, four indices that have rebounded are the consumer, multifarious industry, basic industry, and financial sector indices. The four indices are believed to still have more rooms to bolster IHSG to a higher level.\par \par \uc2 Of the four sector indices driving IHSG to surpass the psychological level 3,500, the consumer stock index books the best performance, soaring 76.19% to 1,182.82.\par \par \uc2 An analyst at PT Asjaya Indosurya Securities Reza Priyambada argued the stronger household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  boosting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth over the past two years had bolstered the four sector indices, which were sensitive to purchasing power, to surpass their pre-crisis levels.\par \par \uc2 "The current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pattern benefits publicly listed companies (Plcs) in the four sectors. The stronger domestic consumption bolsters demand for manufacturing products. Banks also reap up benefit as lending to the sector increases," he said in Jakarta yesterday.\par \par \uc2 Reza also believed amid burdensome regulations, such as an increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  requirement, the performance of the banking industry would not be affected and the industry would still be able to book positive financial performance, thanks to the growing consumer and multifinance loan.\par \par \uc2 He pointed out the steady increase in demand for cars and motorbikes due to strong purchasing power. "With an increase in automotive sales to the multifarious industry sector, demands for products manufactured by other industries are also increasing, such as for products manufactured by publicly listed glass, cable, and tire makers."\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, Reza added, the mining and agriculture sectors, once sustained the stock exchange before the crisis, had not been able to rebound to their pre-crisis record highs.\par \par \uc2 Second-liners\par \par \uc2 An analyst at PT Financorpindo Nusa Helen continued the stronger household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  created a potential for an increase in publicly listed consumer goods companies' profits, prompting investors to pursue consumer goods stocks.\par \par \uc2 "Compared to other sectors, the consumer goods sector is far safer. Moreover, amid the record index high, blue-chip stocks driving the index are overvalued, prompting investors to shift to second-liners, especially consumer goods stocks."\par \par \uc2 The action of investors buying consumer goods stocks creates a flow of foreign investors going to Indonesia Stock Exchange (BEI), which is also in line with global investors' strategy of choosing emerging markets like China and India.\par \par \uc2 Global fund managers, she added, also tended to pursue consumer goods sectors in Indonesia, thanks to the index rally, which was able to provide return to investors compared other emerging markets, which posted negative returns.\par \par \uc2 Besides, she inserted, the high consumer goods stock prices had not been too expensive as many second-liners, such as \uc2 Gudang Garam\uc2 , were available, especially given the less liquid competing shares, such as PT \uc2 HM Sampoerna\uc2  Tbk stock.\par \par \uc2 The expectation of investors has been confirmed by HI performance of publicly listed consumer goods companies. In the first semester of 2010, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  booked IDR1.77 trillion in net profits, soaring 18.39% from IDR1.49 trillion in the first semester of 2009. \uc2 Indofood\uc2  also found its net profit rising 76.4% to IDR1.41 trillion.\par \par \uc2 President Director of Indofood Anthony Salim disclosed the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition was estimated to keep growing, thanks to household consumption, which would positively affect the food industry.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on food represents the largest household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We are in a good position to take advantage of the opportunity."\par \par \uc2 As for the performances of the infrastructure, mining, property, and agriculture indices, which have not rebounded to their pre-crisis levels, an analyst at \uc2 PT Trimegah Securities\uc2  Tbk Handi Hutajaya exposed the pre-crisis \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in general was different from the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Before the crisis, mining and agriculture stocks were steadily breaking records. After the crisis, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shifted to the domestic market, thus, bolstering the performances of consumer, multifarious industry, basic industry, and financial stocks\par \par \uc2 As for the property sector, Handi argued, it was supposed to be automatically be bolstered in the wake of the consumer and multifarious industry stock rallies. Therefore, he suspected there was another precondition unfulfilled.\par \par \uc2 "There has been a kind of mismatch. Property stocks are supposed to increase, but this doesn't happen. This may be attributable to the fact that many investors are still guessing about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead since property investments are long-term in nature."\par \par \uc2 As for the infrastructure sector, which covers the transportation and telco sectors, Handi viewed the performances of some Plcs in the sector were quite convincing, such as the performance of toll road operator \uc2 PT Jasa Marga Tbk\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 However, because the sector also had the largest telco operator \uc2 PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia Tbk\uc2  (Telkom) in it, which had huge index weight but moved sideways, the overall performance of the infrastructure index was considered not as good as other sectors.\par \par \uc2 Regulatory barriers\par \par \uc2 Separately, Deputy Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs for Infrastructure and Regional Development Luky Eko opined the lackluster performance of the infrastructure stock index reflected the reality in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 "Compared to other sectors, such as the mining sector, the infrastructure sector is not bullish since it has been determined more by domestic factors, different from the mining and commodity sectors, which have been influenced more by global factors."\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Indonesia Contractors Association Sudarto said the low infrastructure index growth was caused by the fact that the sector was risky, overregulated, and had high outlook \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "As a result, the sector fails to attract significant interests due to some obstacles, such as land acquisition for toll road projects."\par \par \uc2 In line with Sudarto, Chairperson of the Indonesian National Construction Companies Association Soeharsojo disclosed the construction service industry was still being curbed by regulations, making them unable to bolster infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 According to him, one of the regulatory barriers was the unfinished completion of the Land Acquisition Bill. Once the barrier was addressed, infrastructure development could be accelerated. (Bisnis/ags/05/06/mcd/bsi)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020101004e6a400001\par }