\par\par \b \uc2 Investors still reluctant to enter downstream industries\b0\par\par\uc2 496 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 October 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post    \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Mining companies are showing a low level of enthusiasm to enter the downstream industries, as required by the 2009 Minerals and Coal Law, due to lack of incentive and unclear government policies, the Association of Indonesian Mining Professionals says.\par \par \uc2 The law stipulates that all mining companies are obliged to process their mining products in the country by no later than 2014. The law aims to promote the added value of the mining operations to the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mining association chairman Irwandy Arif told The Jakarta Post that without attractive incentives, he was pessimistic that the companies would seriously comply with the law, moreover, the punishment for infringement was only administrative.\par \par \uc2 "Currently, only a company or two have seriously prepared to enter the downstream industries," he said on the sidelines of the 4th Added Value Mining Indonesia Conference, Workshop and Exhibition at Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Jakarta on Thursday. He added that several companies had developed research or pilot projects to produce derivative products of their commodities, but claimed that none were ready to develop the products on an industrial scale.\par \par \uc2 Irwandy urged the government to create clearer guidelines and policies for companies to develop the downstream industries.\par \par \uc2 He said that a working group from his association was currently assisting the Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry in deliberating a new ministerial decree on detail rules and strategies to develop mining downstream industries.\par \par \uc2 "The draft will contain explanations on mechanisms on how mining companies should process their products," he said. He took the example of the nickel commodity that he proposed had to be processed minimally into ferro or matte nickel.\par \par \uc2 Director General of Manufacturing Industry Base (BIM) for the Industry Ministry Panggah Susanto said that another factor hindering the development of the mining downstream industries was the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  supply of raw materials due to the country's upstream industries low capacity as many mining companies exported their mineral production.\par \par \uc2 "Our industries [including mining] depend heavily on imported raw materials," he said. He added that the government was seeking the best way to develop the capacity of upstream industries in supplying raw materials for downstream ones.\par \par \uc2 Beside the raw materials, energy supply, particularly electricity and gas, also became one decisive factor as to why investors and companies were reluctant to engage in mining downstream industries.\par \par \uc2 To tackle this problem, the government is now promoting the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -private partnership scheme to accelerate the development of infrastructure by focusing on energy and transportation sectors.\par \par \uc2 Panggah said the development of the mining downstream industries was vital to increase the country's product competitiveness. He emphasized that in the current free-trade era, the country had to consistently improve the value and quality of its products to compete with more advance industrialized countries.\par \par \uc2 "We're committed to supporting the development of the downstream industries by facilitating all proposal of incentives, developing human resource quality and promoting investments," he emphasized. (rdf)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101008e6a800011\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Capital Increasingly Flows to Market; Rupiah Nears Strongest Level, Index Hits Record High\b0\par\par\uc2 978 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 October 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Foreign capital inflow to Indonesia is increasing following the bullish regional bourses and relatively controllable domestic inflation amid the tightening of monetary policies implemented by several Asian peers.\par \par \uc2 The Composite Stock Index (IHSG) yesterday hit its record high of 3,618.48, with the daily transaction value reaching the historic high of IDR8.9 trillion, breaking the previous record of IDR8.5 trillion booked on the previous day.\par \par \uc2 The bullish regional bourses, such as indicated by an increase in the MSCI Asia-Pacific index to its two-year high, were supported by soaring major commodity prices, such as crude oil, coal, and CPO prices.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the rupiah exchange rate to the US dollar was traded at IDR8,918 at 16:00 yesterday. The rupiah exchange rate once hit IDR8,900 on September 30, a day before the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) announced that yearly inflation was controllable at 5.08%.\par \par \uc2 The IDR8,900 exchange rate is the stronger since June 2007. So far this year, the rupiah exchange rate to the US dollar has increased 5.2%, following up a 16% increase last year.\par \par \uc2 Yesterday, the index was driven by mining stocks, contributing 93.01%, and infrastructure stocks, contributing 35.18%. Individually, State Gas Company (PGN) stock made the largest contribution, followed by \uc2 PT Adaro Energy Tbk\uc2  and PT \uc2 Indo Tambangraya\uc2  Tbk.\par \par \uc2 Special mention should be given to \uc2 PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia Tbk\uc2  (Telkom), which saw its share price slumping. Amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the Flexi-Esia (\uc2 PT Bakrie Telecom\uc2 ) merger plan, Telkom share price yesterday closed flat at IDR9,050.\par \par \uc2 So far this year, Telkom share fell 4% amid an increase of 38% in IHSG. Historically, the IHSG rally is usually parallel with an increase in Telkom share, which is the second largest market-cap stock after \uc2 PT Astra International Tbk\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Head of Research at PT Valbury Asia Securities Khrisna D. Setiawan explained the receding worries about tighter policies and deeper recession were two factors bolstering capital inflow.\par \par \uc2 "The current liquidity flood prompts investors to switch their funds to assets promising high returns, such as stocks. The choice in turn falls to countries giving high returns and Indonesia is among the countries," he informed in Jakarta yesterday.\par \par \uc2 From Tokyo, President Director of Indonesia Stock Exchange (BEI) Ito Warsito disclosed portfolio investors from Japan had gradually bolstered their investments in Indonesian stocks since they sought high investment returns.\par \par \uc2 "Although the amount of investment is relatively smaller than investments from the US and Europe through fund managers in Hong Kong or Singapore, Japanese investors seeking high growth have gradually switched their investments to Indonesian stocks."\par \par \uc2 Khrisna viewed Indonesia's relatively steady \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political conditions were able to retain foreign funds in the Indonesian market.\par \par \uc2 Although foreign investors could always withdraw their funds, Khrisna forecasted the action would not happen anytime soon.\par \par \uc2 "Logically, foreign investors wick play safe and withdraw their funds if something happens. So far, however, there have not been indications there. They still want to hang around here."\par \par \uc2 Khrisna added more investors flocked to buy stocks since they anticipated the soon-to-be-released Q3 financial performance.\par \par \uc2 An analyst at PT RBS Asia Securities Indonesia Stephan Hasjim forecasted the stock exchange's profit was still potential to grow 16% this year and 20% next year on soaring commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 "Domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -oriented industries, such as the consumer, automotive, retail, banking, and cement industries have surpassed their markets in the first nine months of this year, save for the telco and gas sectors," he exposed in a research report dated October 13.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, sectors sensitive to export demands, such as the coal, metal, and CPO sectors were still under-performed, a trend reversal from 2009.\par \par \uc2 Hasjim viewed coal, banking, and infrastructure stocks would again become the main drivers of the national bourse. BEI's price to earning (P/E) ratio of 15 times was still lower than 19 in 2007.\par \par \uc2 Commodity prices\par \par \uc2 An analyst at PT Reliance Securities Gina Novrina Nasution disclosed the prices of some major commodities were still in an upward trend, thanks to the stronger demands.\par \par \uc2 "Even if there are corrections this year, I think they will still be within the normal range since there are fundamental improvements. The soon-to-be-released third quarter financial statement will also be positive for commodity stocks."\par \par \uc2 In line with Gina, Lanang Trihardian, an analyst at Syailendra Capital, added in general there were improved performances, especially showed by publicly listed mining and plantation companies.\par \par \uc2 Head of Research at PT BNI Securities Tbk Norico Gaman believed the soaring CPO price, which maintained the rallies that publicly listed CPO companies had enjoyed over the past ten days, would not end soon.\par \par \uc2 "CPO price is still potential to go stronger. I project CPO price by the yearend at more than US$1,000 per ton," he said.\par \par \uc2 An analyst at JPMorgan Securities Simone Yeoh argued an increase in CPO price had bolstered forecasts on Asian publicly listed plantation companies' revenues and net profits, hovering at 5%-22%.\par \par \uc2 An economist at \uc2 PT Bank Negara Indonesia Tbk\uc2  (BNI) Rosady T.A Montol said the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) decision of not cutting the benchmark interest rate confirmed how attractive domestic assets were for foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 The rupiah appreciation was also supported by positive sentiments from the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. "This is potential to keep foreign capital flowing to Indonesia, which bolsters the rupiah, the movement of which is monitored closely by BI."\par \par \uc2 However, added Head of Foreign Currency Trading at PT Bank Resona Perdania Lindawati Susanto, BI would not sit idly watching the rupiah appreciation. "The stronger rupiah is attributable to the bullish market. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) will prevent the rupiah from getting stronger," he inserted. (Bisnis/bsi/16/bes/iaa/ags/rar/wiw)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020101020e6af0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
