\par\par \b \uc2 Big fish score by locking PLN in perdition\b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi A. Witular, The Jakarta Post,   \par \uc2 1,810 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 October 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Vested interests within political circles may be at play behind protracted inefficiencies at state power company \uc2 PT Perusahaan Listrik Negara\uc2  (PLN). The Jakarta Post's Rendi A. Witular explores how the company remains a victim of intervention by political elites and their cronies. Here are the stories:\par \par \uc2 When the eldest sister of the spouse of Indonesia's most powerful man walked into PLN headquarters in Jakarta a year or so ago, her visit was said to have been to push PLN's management to buy coal from her mine in Kalimantan -- despite its low quality and the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about supply, according to a former PLN high-ranking official.\par \par \uc2 Apparently greatly concerned with the power of her influence, the PLN management eventually agreed to make a deal -- and the PLN manager who strongly supported the deal was subsequently promoted as a member of the board of directors.\par \par \uc2 Around a year earlier, a contract between PLN and Japanese engineering giant \uc2 Mitsubishi Corporation\uc2  to construct an extended 740-megawatt-power plant in Tanjung Priok, North Jakarta, was allegedly mired in a massive cost inflation.\par \par \uc2 Under the final contract, the plant will cost around US$633 million, 40 percent higher than the $484 million initially agreed eight months earlier.\par \par \uc2 Irregularities in procurement of primary energy for power plants and in the construction of plants, transmission systems, and distribution networks are just part of the problems which have been plaguing PLN for decades.\par \par \uc2 Legislators and critics had again raised the inefficiency issues within the company on Tuesday as a point of argument to reject the government's request for another rise in electricity prices by 10 percent next year.\par \par \uc2 But aside from the inefficiency issues, the PLN performance has been long locked by distortive government policies. Among them is the requirement to sell electricity below its production cost as a populist program to provide cheap electricity for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The discrepancies between production cost and sales prices are then plugged with state \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But the transfer of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  payments to PLN is often late and comes in installment.\par \par \uc2 Operating with such severe restrictions, PLN revenues from electricity sales have never been adequate to cover its operation costs, let alone to make investments in building new power generation plants and transmission and distribution networks,.\par \par \uc2 The result is an acute shortage of power supply which often causes blackouts and hinders \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development.\par \par \uc2 The government has tried to help PLN with additional capital injection but the amount is negligible compared to the company's needs. Worse still, the disbursement of such additional capital reportedly was often tied to vested interests.\par \par \uc2 The much-hyped, first crash program to construct 10,000 MW power plants, mostly financed and constructed by Chinese banks and firms, have become far more problematic than first thought.\par \par \uc2 The program, costing around Rp 170 trillion (US$18 billion), were initiated in 2006 by then vice president Jusuf Kalla and then Coordinating minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Aburizal Bakrie. Both are influential businessmen.\par \par \uc2 Coal-fired plants in Cilacap in Central Java, and Indramayu, Suralaya, and Pelabuhan Ratu in West Java, which are among the first batch of plants under the first 10,000 MW program, now risk standing like white elephants once completed.\par \par \uc2 State Enterprises Minister Mustafa Abubakar blamed bad design and planning in the construction of these plants as causing the trouble.\par \par \uc2 "There is a mismatch between the [Chinese-constructed] plants with the coal-quality specification that will be supplied by local coal companies," said Mustafa last Thursday.\par \par \uc2 He said the problem might force PLN to spend more money and time to adjust the turbines to take local coal, thereby invalidating the claims trumpeted during the tendering process several years ago that Chinese plants were cheaper than others.\par \par \uc2 But PLN's greatest and immediate challenge is to ensure security of coal supply for firing its plants.\par \par \uc2 At the end of August, PLN president director Dahlan Iskan, who just took command of the company nine months earlier, said he would need to import coal, despite the fact that Indonesia has been the world's largest seaborne exporter of coal.\par \par \uc2 Among the causes of coal supply disruption is that the winners in the bidding for feeding the coal into PLN were mostly politically wired brokers with no coal concessions.\par \par \uc2 "We suspect the appointment of these brokers is behind the protracted problems in PLN coal supply," said the deputy chairman of the House's Commission VII for Energy and Mineral Resources, Effendi Simbolon.\par \par \uc2 "The commission has asked the Supreme Audit Agency to investigate coal supply transactions to reveal the mafia behind it," he said.\par \par \uc2 Energy and Mineral Resources Minister Darwin Zahedy Saleh admitted problems in coal supply, but denied brokers were the reason.\par \par \uc2 "Coal suppliers who have secured contracts with PLN are having problems exploiting their \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  because of land disputes. That's why they could not deliver," he said.\par \par \uc2 According to Darwin, coal supplies for PLN are already secured on paper as the government has now enforced the domestic-market obligation (DMO) \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Under the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , around 20 percent of 275 million tons of coal expected to be produced this year will be sold to PLN. However, due to problems above, PLN could not absorb the quota.\par \par \uc2 The government and PLN have long tried to increase the use of coal, gas and other alternative energy sources to fuel power plants, diversifying away from the expensive diesel oil.\par \par \uc2 The electricity generation cost at a oil-fueled plant is Rp 1,300 per killowatt hour (kwh), almost double PLN's Rp 720 per kwh selling price PLN's, while the PLN's average electricity production cost (all coal, gas, oil and hydropower combined) is about Rp 1,100 per kwh.\par \par \uc2 The discrepancy between production cost and selling price has so far been plugged by the electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which this year is estimated at Rp 37.8 trillion.\par \par \uc2 The high production cost, which triggers higher \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  requirements, is caused primarily by the use of diesel oil, accounting for more than 20 percent of the PLN energy mix, according to PLN 2009 annual report.\par \par \uc2 In the first semester of this year, PLN spent Rp 27 trillion procuring oil fuel. The amount is 65 percent of the Rp 41.4 trillion total spent on procuring primary energy.\par \par \uc2 But efforts to reduce the use of oil remains sluggish as every year the composition of oil remains above 22 percent of PLN's energy mix.\par \par \uc2 PLN claims it has to procure more diesel oil because the gas supply to the Muara Tawar power plant in Jakarta has been 50 percent below the originally agreed volume.\par \par \uc2 The company has also burnt more oil to secure supply during the blackout-free program implemented in July 2010.\par \par \uc2 PLN plants can usually accommodate two types of primary energy in case of emergency. Some gas-fired plants and coal-fired plants can be switched to diesel-fired.\par \par \uc2 Commission VII member Achmad Rilyadi is suspicious the stubbornly high proportion of oil use has been engineered by a network of oil importers, who have long benefitted from PLN's dependency on oil.\par \par \uc2 "PLN has never been able to reduce its dependency on oil to below 20 percent of its energy mix," he said. 'They've always claimed shortages in gas supply or disruption in coal delivery as the reason for the use of more oil. Is this the result of poor planning, or is something already engineered to benefit politically wired oil brokers?"\par \par \uc2 But PLN is not solely to blame. \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in government regulations on gas and coal for the domestic market have also played a role in disrupting a smoother flow of cheaper primary energy for the power company.\par \par \uc2 The government is also dragging its feet in streamlining necessary regulations to enable PLN and the private sector to tap the huge \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of geothermal energy.\par \par \uc2 Even though many investors have been vying for the geothermal projects, PLN cannot yet sign any power purchase deal unless there is a presidential decree as its legal foundation, according to Darwin.\par \par \uc2 "It's still being deliberated, but it will be sooner than later," said Darwin.\par \par \uc2 Electricity sector analyst Fabby Tumiwa, the executive director of Institute for Essential Services Reform, said the problems plaguing PLN have become widely known for a long time but hardly anything has been done to resolve them.\par \par \uc2 He blamed the government's ignorance on the magnitude of the problems. A lack of coordination among government agencies also plays a role in the failure to rapidly solve the structural problems.\par \par \uc2 Fabby also highlighted the possibility of vested interests in keeping PLN in its current state, given its huge \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  on procurements, which tempts many to take a slice of the cake.\par \par \uc2 "PLN's capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  reaches around Rp 60 trillion annually, while its operational \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  tops around Rp 100 trillion. These are a huge cake that lures many."\par \par \uc2 "Any attempts to reform the electricity sector may disturb numerous vested interests which have already taken root in PLN," he said.\par \par \uc2 It is allegedly common for politicians and politically wired businessmen to intervene in setting the reform agenda for the PLN to their advantage.\par \par \uc2 "The selection for PLN top management should be transparent, based on competency and free of political influence. But I don't see it happening right now," said member of commission VII Satya Yudha.\par \par \uc2 The appointment of media tycoon Dahlan Iskan, a former journalist, as the president director or chief executive officer of PLN is mired with allegations of vested interests.\par \par \uc2 Dahlan is known to have close ties with fellow tycoon Chairul Tanjung, whose business empire Para Group is also active in the power business.\par \par \uc2 In early 2009, Dahlan launched a campaign to promote Chairul as vice president to pair with President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, who was at the time looking for a partner for the general election.\par \par \uc2 Dahlan, who has no prior experience in the electricity sector aside from having small independent power plants, declined an interview request.\par \par \uc2 Aside from Dahlan, PLN commissioner Abdul Aziz also has close ties to politically wired Chairul. Abdul was once an executive for the Chairul Tanjung Foundation.\par \par \uc2 Minister Mustafa in an interview late last year said he appointed Abdul as his special staff as well as a would-be PLN commissioner after consulting with Chairul.\par \par \uc2 "I did ask for a permission from Chairul if I can use Abdul, whom I've known for years," said Mustafa.\par \par \uc2 Chairul, who is also the chairman of National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Council and one of President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's supporters during the 2009 general election, denied he would exploit his close connections to Dahlan to boost his electricity business.\par \par \uc2 "I've never taken any advantage of Dahlan or the government to help out with my business," said Chairul on Aug. 5 at the Bogor Presidential Palace.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101027e6ar0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 OECD Suggests Indonesia Eliminating  \highlight22\uc2 Subsidy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 408 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 November 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The Organization of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development (OECD) suggests the Indonesian government fulfilling its commitment to eliminate fossil fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by 2014 and reduce electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This is one of the organization's recommendations based on the survey of the 2010 Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indonesia has been partnering with the OECD since 2000.\par \par \uc2 The OECD, which has as its members governments from 30 countries adopting market democracy, views Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance from 2009-2010 has been good enough to get out of the global crisis. The OECD appreciates that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2009 was able to grow by 4.6%, the third largest among the G-20 countries after China and India.\par \par \uc2 However, there are some flaws that may curb \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress, such as those related to \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies. The organization mentions that it is important to widely socialize the benefit of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  lift and cash transfer to more appropriate target groups.\par \par \uc2 The OECD urges the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) to raise the benchmark interest rate by the yearend to meet the inflation target for 2011.\par \par \uc2 As to investment, the OECD also spotlights the importance of stronger investments in the infrastructure sector to deal with growth barriers. Therefore, investment funds in the sector are considered necessary.\par \par \uc2 The organization adds there are three things that the government needs to address. First, the government needs to create legal certainty and consistent investment policies.\par \par \uc2 Second, the government needs to reduce barriers curbing foreign investments. Third, the government needs to develop policies to facilitate and promote the link between foreign investments and the local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As to macroeconomic conditions, the OECD suggests Indonesia cutting inflationary target and strengthening monetary policies.\par \par \uc2 Not b\par \par \uc2 inding\par \par \uc2 In response to that, Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Hatta Rajasa stated the recommendations from the OECD, including \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  removal and benchmark interest rate hikes, were not binding to be complied with.\par \par \uc2 Besides, he added, the recommended \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  removal had been in line with the government's roadmap.\par \par \uc2 However, Bambang P. S. Brodjonegoro, the Director of the Islamic Research and Training Institute at the Islamic Development Bank, viewed the government needed to respond to the OECD's recommendations, especially those regarding the transfer from price \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to targeted one.\par \par \uc2 A member of the House Commission VII M. Romahurmuziy argued the OECD's oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  removal was made in the perspective of corporations caused by the organization's business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (Bisnis/agi//dea/nti/14)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020101102e6b200002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
