\par\par \b \uc2 Obama's visit: Symbolic or substantive?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,065 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 November 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 When US President Barack Obama left Washington for a visit to Asia and Indonesia, this week, he must not have been in the best mood.\par \par \uc2 Americans angry with high unemployment and the weak US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery had delivered their verdict in the mid-term election by condemning the Democratic party and ousting them from their former majority position in Congress.\par \par \uc2 The bitter fight on the health insurance bill early this year contributed to the continued enmity between Democrats and Republicans, throwing the prospect of a real US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery into greater \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The battle to pass the health insurance bill in Congress has consumed much of Obama's energy and political capital, and has distracted his attention from the American people's number one concern: the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It was also one reason Obama canceled his planned visit to Indonesia last June.\par \par \uc2 The US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to jump start growth and lift itself out of the doldrums. But the Republicans insist on reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits, which are already huge and unsustainable in the long term.\par \par \uc2 The US hopes that increasing exports could boost the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but this means asking its trade partners to increase their imports from the US by appreciating their currencies against US dollar.\par \par \uc2 The possibility that America's trading partners would be willing to appreciate their currencies is slim, because they also have problems with their own economies.\par \par \uc2 The Federal Reserve has just made a risky gamble with its decision to purchase US$600 billion worth of government securities.\par \par \uc2 The main goal of this decision, known popularly as quantitative easing, or QE, is to revive the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery by pushing long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  lower.\par \par \uc2 For Obama, the hope for a stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and a reduction in unemployment rates could come from the success of the Fed QE.\par \par \uc2 This is because \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , another \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  option that could stimulate growth, would have little chance of passing in the new Congress where the Republican majority is adamant about reducing the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This is the second time the Fed has used this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  instrument. The first QE, introduced in March 2009, was worth more than twice the QE2 but still failed to accelerate recovery and reduce unemployment.\par \par \uc2 Markets have begun voicing their skepticism over whether the QE2 would deliver the expected results this time.\par \par \uc2 Obama also realized that QE2 would produce undesirable effects for emerging economies, including Indonesia. Quantitative easing means that the Fed will pump money into the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As liquidity expands, long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would go down, and the resulting interest rate differentials would drive investors to move their money to emerging economies, including Indonesia, where returns are still more attractive.\par \par \uc2 The flood of capital into emerging economies would drive up asset prices, and if this is not managed properly it could produce an asset price bubble that could eventually plunge the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into recession.\par \par \uc2 An expanded US dollar supply would drive its value down, making the currencies of its trading partners appreciate against the US dollar. If governments in emerging economies do not respond, their\par \par \uc2 exports would lose their competitive strength and imports would unduly rise, throwing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into disarray.\par \par \uc2 Emerging economies are then faced with unpleasant choices, either to impose capital controls or\par \par \uc2 to engage in competitive currency devaluation.\par \par \uc2 Obama's visit to Indonesia is taking place when the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is decoupling itself from the influence of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The ability of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to weather the disastrous impacts of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis last year was testimony to its low exposure to the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  becomes more integrated with its Asian neighbors, there has been shift in its relationship with the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indonesia trades more with and receives more investment from the Asian region.\par \par \uc2 The direct role of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is receding, but is still significant.\par \par \uc2 This year Americans bought 10.5 percent of Indonesia's exports, down from 12.3 percent in 2007, before the global crisis.\par \par \uc2 Over the same period, the Chinese bought the same amount of Indonesian exports, but up from 7.3 percent in 2007.\par \par \uc2 Despite the weak recovery in the US and the rupiah appreciation this year, Indonesian exports to the US rose by 30 percent. This compares with the 56 percent export jump to China.\par \par \uc2 This year the US supplied only 9 percent of Indonesia's imports, a figure unchanged from 2007. Excluding oil and gas, US investment in Indonesia is minor compared with investment from other countries.\par \par \uc2 In 2007, investment by US companies in Indonesia totaled $13 billion, one third of the total foreign investment.\par \par \uc2 As Indonesia has increasingly shifted its foreign debt to multilateral agencies, the amount bilateral debt from the US has become insignificant.\par \par \uc2 The amount outstanding is now $1.3 billion, a mere 2.2 percent of total Indonesian foreign debt. One of the issues that should be raised during Obama's visit is the US commitment to provide $1 billion fund to help emerging economies fight climate change. Indonesia has expressed interest in these funds to fight deforestation and reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\par \par \uc2 As Indonesia is one of four countries that Obama will be visiting, it seems that there is no special meaning attached to the Indonesian visit.\par \par \uc2 India, the first country Obama is visiting, has more substantive and strategic issues with the US compared to Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 India is growing restless with what is happening in Pakistan and Afghanistan, and the US needs India as a partner to deal with instability in the region.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has been looking forward to Obama's visit, and is ready to extend its warmest welcome, as if to welcome back a family member who has been away for so long.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is a place where Obama spent four years of his childhood and where he first started his education. Indonesians are proud that\par \par \uc2 one of the most popular US presidents in history has a close cultural affinity with Indonesia, and has acquired Asian, and especially Muslim, sensibilities.\par \par \uc2 Obama's visit to Indonesia, the largest Muslim-majority nation in the world, would acquire a symbolic meaning for his overture in bridging the great divide between the West and Islam. It is also symbolic for his ever-present Indonesian family.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101109e6b90000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
