\par\par \b \uc2 Managing exogenous shocks in Indonesia\b0\par\par\uc2 1,078 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 November 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Kumba Digdowiseiso, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Most economists find it difficult to devise an appropriate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  when they deal with an unpredictable event that affects an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Natural disasters are one of the unexpected factors which economics cannot explain, but which may have a significant impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth as well as on loss of life.\par \par \uc2 Major catastrophic events from the Wasior flash flood in Papua, to the unprecedented floods in Jakarta, to the volcanic eruption of Mount Merapi in Central Java and finally the tsunami that swept away part of the population of Mentawai have resulted not only in loss of human life and material costs but have also drawn \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and global attention.\par \par \uc2 In its assessment report on disaster risk reduction, the World Bank (2009) placed Indonesia as\par \par \uc2 a country with 40 percent of the population at risk from frequent multiple hazards such as earthquakes, tsunamis, volcanic eruptions, floods, landslides, droughts and forest fires.\par \par \uc2 In the case of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks, the high frequency of such disasters creates an enormous burden on government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  to rebuild \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities and infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 The World Bank further analyzed that there are two factors that make our people susceptible to large-scale disasters.\par \par \uc2 First, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in Indonesia has shown a strong correlation with higher urbanization. By 2008, at least 50 percent of the population was living in the cities and urban areas were increasing at 4.4 percent per year, well above average national population growth.\par \par \uc2 This puts more than 110 million people in around 60 cities mostly located in coastal areas, increasing the vulnerability of the population.\par \par \uc2 Second, the high rate of urbanization in Indonesia coupled with limited capacity of urban centers to provide adequate shelter and infrastructure has led to the emergence of many unplanned settlements.\par \par \uc2 Poor enforcement of land use zoning has in turn led to many hazard-prone locations becoming subject to human settlement.\par \par \uc2 Thus, the combination of weak governance, widespread new settlement and inadequate infrastructure potentially causes major problems for Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 We may also take into consideration socio-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors like \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development measured by per-capita GDP and institutional factors such as government stability and investment climate in determining a society's vulnerability against natural hazards.\par \par \uc2 I believe that all these factors implicitly may provide a level of ex-ante insurance to mitigate risks bearing in mind many disasters in Indonesia have destroyed uninsured \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure and private homes.\par \par \uc2 Ironically, the government apparently do not have a concise action plan for mitigating disaster including reflecting on the risk profile of Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 We know that Indonesia is highly vulnerable to earthquakes and volcanic eruptions because we are in the earthquake belt and the Pacific ring-of-fire.\par \par \uc2 Also, a high rainfall regime in the western area of Indonesia and a dry zone in some eastern provinces potentially can lead to floods and droughts.\par \par \uc2 Rather, in many cases, the government prefers to choose ex-post disaster financing to cope with the impact of disaster.\par \par \uc2 So, is ex-post disaster financing through government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  and donors better than ex-ante disaster financing through insurance? The University of Yale sociologist, Charles Perrow (2007), shows that \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should focus on the targets concentrated in coastal areas, and other infrastructures in disaster prone locations.\par \par \uc2 This suggestion came from the fact that more ex-post assistance generates a "Samaritan's dilemma", which increases risk-taking behavior and a reluctance to purchase insurance when aid is likely to be provided, should disaster strike.\par \par \uc2 But, two economists from the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania, Mark Pauly and Howard\par \par \uc2 Kunreuther (2009), noted that there are some problems associated with exante insurance coverage in the event of large disaster.\par \par \uc2 First, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  with regard to the magnitude of potential losses. Second, there can be highly bunched risks among the insured.\par \par \uc2 Third, there could be moral hazards related to excessive risk-taking by the insured.\par \par \uc2 Last, an adverse selection of insured parties could be caused by imperfect information.\par \par \uc2 Those problems do not stop if we are pushed to implement disaster insurance.\par \par \uc2 First, our insurance markets have been insufficiently developed due to risk exposure and weak infrastructure, which often limits the supply of insurance.\par \par \uc2 Also, high poverty and unemployment rates in the midst of lack of good information contribute to a low demand for insurance.\par \par \uc2 Finally, weak incentives for political leadership with a short attention span to enter into insurance contracts creates political resistance to purchasing insurance.\par \par \uc2 Generally, disasters are viewed by \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers as natural phenomena, and they usually explain events in those terms.\par \par \uc2 Take the behavior of Jakarta Governor Fauzi Bowo who always blames rain as the cause of floods.\par \par \uc2 From the above arguments, it can be seen that neither ex-post nor ex-ante disaster financing necessarily provides the best solution. Based on the difficulties of financing large-scale disasters from local resources, I support the view of Howard Kunreuther and Joanne Linnerooth-Bayer (2002) that catastrophe bonds could be included as a risk-transfer mechanism as a substitute for reinsurance contracts in producing a source of contingent capital for disaster relief and recovery in developing countries like Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 As an instrument for reinsurance companies, this can hedge the risk of insolvency and overcome the limitations of traditional sources of disaster aid.\par \par \uc2 The nature of risk-transfer has many advantages over ex-post disaster financing, both short-term and long-term, because it provides fast access to capital, and avoids budgetary diversions as well as additional loans.\par \par \uc2 Another important advantage is that hedging instruments can be designed to deliver incentives for disaster planning and mitigation.\par \par \uc2 For example, weather derivative contracts are one type of hedging instrument that have begun to emerge in many disaster-prone countries such as the US and Japan, also in under-developed countries with severe weather like Malawi, as a substitute for yield-based crop insurance.\par \par \uc2 This type of insurance can actually be used to manage weather-related crop risks in Indonesia where indemnity payments are based on rainfall levels and can help hedge against drought or excessive rainfall.\par \par \uc2 The series of disasters that just happened in Indonesia could provide an important lesson for our government to lessen negative impacts in the future.\par \par \uc2 To pursue mitigation strategies before such events occur could be the ideal solution.\par \par \uc2 The writer, a graduate of the University of Adelaide, Australia, is a lecturer at National University, Jakarta, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  researcher at Transparency International Indonesia. The opinions expressed are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101111e6bb0000w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
