\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: GDP growth trend: Brighter days ahead\b0\par\par\uc2 869 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 November 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Andry Asmoro, Bahana Securities,\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's recent GDP data was undoubtedly an eyebrow raiser for most amid expectations of continued acceleration in growth. At 5.8 percent year-on-year (y-y), the GDP in the third quarter of this year (3Q10) was markedly well below market consensus of 6.4 percent and lower than the 2Q10 growth of 6.2 percent y-y. However, this is very much in line with our expectation, and on target to achieve our 2010-end GDP growth forecast of 6.0 percent.\par \par \uc2 Apart from a slowdown in exports (3Q10: +25 percent y-y; 2Q10: +32 percent y-y), lower GDP growth was partly due to unexpectedly flat private consumption of 5.2 percent y-y in 3Q10, compared to 5.0 percent in 2Q10.\par \par \uc2 However, this is also in line with our recent findings on listed Indonesian consumer corporates, which experienced both operating and bottom line deterioration. Note that normally Indonesia's consumer sector tends to be much more resilient even in the most adverse of conditions.\par \par \uc2 In 3Q10, even \uc2 Unilever\uc2 , Indonesia's consumer power-house, cited lower volumes on the back of\par \par \uc2 higher basic foods prices and installment purchases of bigger ticket items such as motorcycles, TVs and mobile phones.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, Ramayana, Indonesia's largest low-end department stores also booked September sales of Rp 941 billion, 10.6 percent below the company's internal target of Rp 1,050 billion, after hitting Rp 725 billion in the first 9 days of the month, leading up to Lebaran (Idul Fitri) holidays. This meant a rapid deceleration in the days post Lebaran. It is worth noting that August sales of Rp 872 billion also fell 8 percent short of the company's estimate. RALS has cited rainy days as the culprit in dampening shopping activities as its customers are motorcycle owners who prefer to stay home when conditions are wet.\par \par \uc2 With the GDP growth at 5.9 percent in the first nine months of this year, we expect 4Q10 GDP\par \par \uc2 growth to pick up slightly to the 6.2 percent level to bring it in line with our full-year GDP growth estimate of 6 percent.\par \par \uc2 In 2011, we expect consensus could again be disappointed as output, particularly in 1Q and 2Q next year, on the back of adverse weather (unusually heavy rains) impacting the agriculture sector and mining. On the \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  side, the 3Q10 story of little change could persist while net foreign trade could be a drag on GDP change, as exports increased more slowly than imports due to continued global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 On a more positive note, investment grew 7 percent q-q in 3Q10, the highest growth since 3Q04.\par \par \uc2 This was in line with the Investment Coordinating Board's (BKPM) data of direct (domestic & foreign) investment realization growth of 33.4 percent y-y in 3Q10 to Rp 149.6 trillion. As of 3Q10, the investment realization had reached 93.4\par \par \uc2 percent of the 2010 target of Rp 160 trillion. Better foreign direct investment of US$2.5 billion level, up from $1.9 billion in 2Q10, was also presented in the current balance of payment (BOP) data.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, we saw a broader-based q-q \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth based on industry, which should continue to improve going into 4Q10, supported by transportation & communication industry, which managed to book the highest growth in 3Q10. However, other two sectors that contributed around 52 percent of Indonesia's total employment also improved with the agriculture sector booking 6 percent q-q growth, while we saw faster growth of 2.6 percent q-q from 2.1 percent in 2Q10 in the manufacturing sector. Better growth is very much needed to meet the government's unemployment rate target of 7.5 percent in 2010.\par \par \uc2 Finally, on the trade front, trade surplus was still robust even though the amount was relatively volatile. As of September, the year-to-date export growth reached 38.2 percent compared to the same\par \par \uc2 period last year. In the BOP, the merchandise trade surplus widened to $9.1 billion vis-?-vis $8.6 billion in 2Q10.\par \par \uc2 In sum, heavy rain disrupting 3Q10 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would not derail our 2010 GDP growth of 6.0 percent. This will be supported by government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which tends to be disbursed in the last quarter. The government stated that the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  realization had only reached round 61 percent of the targeted Rp 1,126 trillion. With some 95 percent of the estimated \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be disbursed this year, the amount of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 4Q10 would reach around Rp 390 trillion.\par \par \uc2 Another support will stem from investment as realization is expected to exceed the government's target, buoyed by Chinese trade and investment delegation's plan to invest USD6.6b in various\par \par \uc2 Indonesian infrastructure and development projects.\par \par \uc2 Thus, going into 2011, infrastructure improvement schemes are clearly creating new investment opportunities. This coupled with improved macro \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making and stable political environment; we believe that the risk to our 6.1 percent GDP growth estimate for next year is skewed to the upside.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at PT Bahana Securities.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101111e6bb0001o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoa