\par\par \b \uc2 No extreme capital control: Govt\b0\par\par\uc2 557 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 November 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The government ruled out Thursday the possibility of using a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  instrument to cope with the feared sudden reversal of foreign funds, saying that it will instead introduce high-yielding debt notes to ensure they stay even longer.\par \par \uc2 Speaking to reporters following a coordinating meeting with \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Jakarta, Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister Hatta Rajasa said instead of using extreme capital control such as \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it would better for the country to offer high-return investment instruments in coping with the reversal of the foreign funds.\par \par \uc2 The meeting discussed possible measures in dealing with the influx of foreign funds amid a warning that developing nations, such as Indonesia which has become a favorite destination for hot money from developed countries, should take "action" to cope with their negative impact such as creating a market bubble, and their possible sudden reversal in the event of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Hatta acknowledged that the massive influx of foreign funds could have a negative impact on the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  such as the unrealistic increase in asset prices. In order to prevent the bubble \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said, the foreign funds should be directed to productive debt instruments such as infrastructure bonds.\par \par \uc2 "Issuing infrastructure bonds will help finance and build our infrastructure projects, so capital inflow can enter the real sector. Why not? That's a good example [of what they have] in India," Hatta told reporters after the meeting at BI offices in Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 Mid this year, India announced a plan to offer a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentive to foreign investors buying its infrastructure bonds to cope with the fund shortage of the country's infrastructure development. According to Hatta, the issuance of such infrastructure bonds could be effective in directing foreign funds into a more productive sector such as infrastructure projects.\par \par \uc2 International financial agencies such as the World Bank has warned developing nations to issue capital control to minimize negative impacts of the foreign fund inflows in their countries. The most feared risk of the foreign capital inflow is their sudden reversal, which can take place if there is a disruption to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Hatta said that Indonesia could instead take advantage of the foreign funds to strengthen its capacity to finance infrastructure projects, one of the government's main priorities in accelerating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. He also said that investment in infrastructure projects need boosting. "Don't let all of the funds be stacked in SUN [government bonds] and SBI [BI certificates]," he added.\par \par \uc2 As of September of this year, an estimated US$12 billion in foreign funds have flown into the country's stock and debt markets, totaling foreign funds share in stocks at 67 percent up to the same period. Foreigners also account for 31.5 percent of funds placed at SUN and 29.6 percent at SBI, the latest BI data shows.\par \par \uc2 Amid lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the developed nations, foreign investors have shifted their funds to the emerging markets, including Indonesia, China and India, which offer more stable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals and higher returns on investments.\par \par \uc2 Both Hatta and Finance Minister Agus Martowardojo declined to comment on possibilities of foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds that flood into the country, but said that it was important to shift the funds to longer-dated investments, especially in the real sector. (est)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101119e6bj0001g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
