\par\par \b \uc2 Editorial: Watching the Irish crisis\b0\par\par\uc2 533 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 November 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Even though the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the European \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the European Commission were close to a final agreement on tens of billions of dollars in loans to bail out Irish banks, Indonesia, notably its \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , should closely watch developments in the eurozone.\par \par \uc2 If \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues over whether Ireland would default on its debts, doubt contagion could spread to debt markets in Portugal and Spain, a far larger \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  than Ireland. If that happens, the European Union would not be able to bail out Spain, causing a systemic threat to overall European \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability.\par \par \uc2 Last April when Greece suffered a similar financial debacle, almost US$6 billion in foreign portfolio funds flew out of Indonesia's financial market in a matter of days.\par \par \uc2 Most analysts agree the Irish crisis is far more serious for the eurozone than the Greek situation.\par \par \uc2 As a similarly sudden reverse capital flow could happen again, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) should gear up for such a possibility, especially because the bulk of the almost $90 billion it held in foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  consisted of short-term portfolio capital.\par \par \uc2 The debt woes in Ireland may stimulate further inflows of short-term capital to Indonesia, and such a fund injection could be both a blessing and "curse", depending on market sentiment and the condition of Indonesia's financial market.\par \par \uc2 Up to now, the 6 percentage point interest rate differential offered by BI's debt papers (SBI) has been the main factor pulling in foreign funds. But since Indonesia has not yet achieved an investment-grade rating in terms of sovereign risk, the investments have gone mostly to short-tenure instruments.\par \par \uc2 Fears that the Irish government will be unable to shoulder the mounting costs of rescuing its troubled banks have eroded market confidence in the country's financial viability over the past week, and reignited concerns about other members of the 16-country eurozone.\par \par \uc2 As investors have started selling Irish bonds, a surge in bond yields could drag other countries into a similar bind. In fact, anxiety about Ireland has caused jitters in other financially shaky eurozone countries.\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday, Portugal shelled out a lofty interest rate to attract investors in a routine government bond auction. But a cause of great concern is the fact that Portugal had a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 9.3 percent of gross domestic product last year, the highest in the euro region after Ireland, Greece and Spain.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has taken a series of measures in coping with the torrent of capital inflows, including selling only longer-tenure bonds (six to 12 months) and raising the primary reserve requirement to 8 percent to soak up excess liquidity in the banking system.\par \par \uc2 But the most effective way of encouraging foreign capital to stay much longer in Indonesia is by encouraging foreign direct investment through a more conducive business climate. Money invested in fixed assets, such as factories, is not as vulnerable to the wild volatility of short-term funds which could fly out of country at the slightest sign of trouble.\par \par \uc2 The distressed banking industry in Ireland should also teach \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  a good lesson for avoiding a similar fiasco.\