\par\par \b \uc2 Conserving our natural capital\b0\par\par\uc2 954 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Wiryono , Queensland\par \par \uc2 In the second half of 2010 we experienced a series of natural disasters within a short period of time, such as flooding in Papua, an earthquake and tsunami in West Sumatra and volcanic eruption in Central Java that claimed many lives.\par \par \uc2 By now we must be aware that we, humans, are part of nature and consequently, our life is absolutely dependent on natural conditions. Despite experiencing natural disasters, in general, we are fortunate to be blessed with rich natural resources.\par \par \uc2 Our terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems with their biological and geological resources constitute our natural capital upon which our success and even survival as a nation depend. Our natural capital provides ecosystem services essential to our well being.\par \par \uc2 The Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (2005), written by many experts from reputed international institutions such as FAO, UNEP, World Bank, UN University and many universities, classifies ecosystem services into four categories, namely provisioning services (producing food, fiber, fuel, water, etc.), regulating services (regulating climate, air quality, water purification, pollination, etc.) cultural services (providing spiritual, educational, aesthetical values, etc.) and supporting services (soil formation, photosynthesis, water cycling and nutrient cycling).\par \par \uc2 All services are important and interrelated. For example, the presence of pollinators (regulating service) and soil nutrient (supporting service) are important for the maintenance of food crop productivity (provisioning service).\par \par \uc2 However, most resource management decisions are determined mostly by provisioning services because they yield marketable goods. Other services usually are not traded on the market and therefore have no price or are at least undervalued.\par \par \uc2 Fortunately, our government legally recognizes the many services of the ecosystems. We have designated some of our terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems as conservation areas.\par \par \uc2 Law No. 41/1999 on forestry explicitly defines a forest as an ecosystem. Realizing that a forest ecosystem has many functions, we have designated more than 30 percent of our forests as conservation forests and protected forests. No logging is allowed in these two forest categories.\par \par \uc2 In practice, however, we perceive forests mainly as timber producers and seas as fish producers. As a\par \par \uc2 result, our forests and seas have been exploited excessively, legally and illegally, which jeopardizes their sustainability.\par \par \uc2 Our market-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system fails to value other ecosystem services. In developed countries and in Java, the cultural services in the form of recreation and tourism have resulted in monetary value, but in many areas in Indonesia, most cultural values have not yielded money.\par \par \uc2 To some degree, the regulating services are beginning to get a global market value through carbon trading. But the implementation of carbon trading may take a long time and its beneficial impact to a local community remains to be seen.\par \par \uc2 Attempts have been made to make an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  valuation of ecosystem services. Costanza et al in 1987 published an article in the British journal Nature stating that the estimated \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value of the world's ecosystem services was in the range of US$16 trillion to $54 trillion annually, with an average of $33 trillion per annum.\par \par \uc2 Because of the nature of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , this must be considered a minimum estimate. Global GNP at that time was around $18 trillion per year. Most of those values, however, are not economically measured because they have no price.\par \par \uc2 At the national level, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  valuation of conservation areas has been done. For example, the total \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value of Leuser National Park over the period of 2000-2030, with a 4 percent discount rate, is: $7.0 billion under the "deforestation scenario", $9.5 billion under the "conservation scenario" and $9.1 billion under the "selective utilization scenario" (Vanbeukering et al., 2003).\par \par \uc2 Although the conservation scenario has the highest value and benefits all stakeholders, the park is still under serious threat of illegal logging and encroachment, because the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value in the conservation scenario is not in the form of cash money but mostly in the form of water supply, flood prevention and supporting services for agriculture. Those values are not direct, while cutting timber or converting the forest into plantations will yield cash.\par \par \uc2 The failure of our market-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system to value non-marketable ecosystem services has caused degradation of our natural capital, which may jeopardize the flow of ecosystem services.\par \par \uc2 At the global level, according to the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment, 60 percent of the ecosystem services are being degraded or used unsustainably.\par \par \uc2 If the trend continues, the degradation of ecosystem services may grow significantly worse and prevent the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals.\par \par \uc2 Former World Bank economist Herman Daly believes that at present, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development is not limited by lack of human-made capital, but of natural capital (Hawken et al., 2010).\par \par \uc2 To achieve sustainable development, it is imperative that we conserve our natural capital in order to maintain the flow of ecosystem services. Several measures must be taken.\par \par \uc2 To prevent excessive use of natural resources we can increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the exploitation of natural resources and reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , giving a signal to the market that our natural resources are getting scarcer. On the other hand, we must give incentives for the development of technologies and management practices to use resources more efficiently and to reduce pollution.\par \par \uc2 But most important is to educate businesspeople and policymakers of the intangible benefits of ecosystem services. Although at present they have little \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value, in fact their total value is infinite. For without the continuing flow of ecosystem services, our economies will come to a halt.\par \par \uc2 Conserving our natural capital is essential for the sustainability of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development to ensure the well-being of our growing population.\par \par \uc2 The writer is a lecturer at the University of Bengkulu's School of Forestry and currently writing a book at James Cook University in Queensland, Australia.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101203e6c30000o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
