\par\par \b \uc2 Labor  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties \highlight\uc2  off-putting: Apindo\b0\par\par\uc2 Rngga D. Fadillah, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 524 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will unlikely expand by more than 6 percent next year, contrary to government expectations, as unresolved labor issues will continue to hamper new investment activities, a prominent businessman says.\par \par \uc2 The chairman of the Indonesian Businessmen Association (Apindo), Sofjan Wanandi, said Friday that legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over labor problems were turning off foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 "Given this problem, it would be good if we could maintain this year's growth next year," he told the The Jakarta Post.\par \par \uc2 The World Bank revised its estimate for Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2010 from 6.0 percent to 5.9 percent. However, the government says it is still optimistic growth can reach 6.0 percent by the end of this year, and 6.4 percent in 2011.\par \par \uc2 The first factor impeding the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and now a major constraint for investments to enter the country, Sofjan said, was legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly concerning labor regulations.\par \par \uc2 "Laborer demonstrations in the country have been getting more extreme recently. The problems appear to be due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in regulations on labor such as outsourcing and minimum wages," he said.\par \par \uc2 Actually both businessmen and laborers dislike outsourcing, but there is no \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  that ensures the productivity of laborers if they are made permanent employees of 