\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesia's politics of laissez-faire\b0\par\par\uc2 1,171 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Meidyatama Suryodiningrat, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 "Muddling through" has been a term too often associated with Indonesia. As some would say: "This country is good at muddling through and surviving, but not really good at thriving".\par \par \uc2 But during the past year there has been remarkably peaked interest from investors and analysts looking at the country. In the United States and Europe, a rediscovery of Indonesia has emerged as something both attractive and potential.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's inclusion in the G20 was a significant sign of the bestowed recognition as others openly talked about Indonesia being included as part of the so-called "BRIC" group of major emerging nations.\par \par \uc2 Two strong assets that were identified was the democratic political stability in the country and the strength of the domestic market. With impressive performances in various \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators, it was not surprising that Indonesia was being perceived in a favorable light.\par \par \uc2 So it is often surprising to outsiders that Indonesians often seem so downcast on their government despite the seemingly positive trends.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps Indonesians are too hard on themselves. And perhaps, too, they forget that the nation kissed many frogs in search of a prince before settling on President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono.\par \par \uc2 Or it could be that the concerns on the ground do not match the theoretical realities represented by the numbers that analysts look at.\par \par \uc2 These are the contradictions that make up Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Just over a year after he was re-elected, the sense of exasperation prevailing among the middle class and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  players is such that one would be forgiven for forgetting that he was someone who twice received an overwhelming majority at the polls.\par \par \uc2 It is not that people believe he (and his administration) is governing badly, but he is simply not governing enough!\par \par \uc2 While the teams assembled by Vice President Boediono and Presidential Unit for the Management of Programs (UKP3) chairman Kuntoro Mangkusubroto are a ground zero for potential good initiatives, few seem to be taken to the level of implementation as approval from the President remains in-waiting.\par \par \uc2 This laissez-faire state of affairs in politics -- no vision, a lack of clear direction and very little decision-making -- that highlighted Yudhoyono's first year back at the palace will likely be a hallmark of 2011 again.\par \par \uc2 By all accounts, this administration can likely get away with it. Simply on the foundations of a robust and strong domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  there is no reason to believe that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not grow with similar vigor in 2011 as it did a year earlier at around the 6 percent mark.\par \par \uc2 Two things, however, could upset the easy-as-you-go style of management. This first would be a hefty rise in basic food prices, in particular rice going beyond the Rp 10,000 per kilogram psychological barrier. The second would be the expected price rise of oil in the world market -- expected to be US$100 per barrel -- in 2011. The increase would expand fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a point that is unmanageable for the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are able to sustain these shocks, but for how long?\par \par \uc2 Fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and basic commodities are always sparks for social unrest and therefore political instability. A government that has been dormant for so long will have to be shocked into action.\par \par \uc2 One important development at the tail-end of 2010 has been the passing of a new law on political parties that will come into effect in mid-January 2011. The introduction of the new law will be a pre-start signal for political parties ahead of the 2014 general election.\par \par \uc2 Expect more affirmative moves from groups like the National Democrat movement as they likely to prepare for the evolution into a political party.\par \par \uc2 As the situation on the ground slowly begins to crystallize, watch for the reactions of both Yudhoyono and his Democratic Party, along with the Golkar Party.\par \par \uc2 If the joint secretariat, headed by Golkar chairman Aburizal Bakrie, can work together then it could bode well for government programs in 2011. If not, then the already fragile alliance may only last in name up to 2014.\par \par \uc2 Of course, a common "foe" like National Democrat chairman Surya Paloh may be a catalyst for Golkar and the Democratic Party to accommodate each other. Especially if the latter is holding more political aces at the moment than the former.\par \par \uc2 These aces (or skeletons in the closest) are not to be drawn in 2011. Rather, they represent bargaining chips to keep one or the other in check.\par \par \uc2 For the First Family, the primary task will be to decide in the next two years whom the next patriarch will be, as Yudhoyono is constitutionally ineligible to run for a third consecutive term.\par \par \uc2 All eyes will be on potential new challenges and making sure they make no significant headway that could undermine the rise of the house of Yudhoyono.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps though the most worrying aspect within Indonesian politics is the creeping rise of Islamic conservatism. With the number of Islamic based shariah-bylaws increasing, acts of thuggery against freedom of worship and the barely effective response from authorities, right-wing groups are becoming emboldened and receiving undue legitimacy.\par \par \uc2 For the first time in more than a decade, there is reason to be concerned.\par \par \uc2 In the past there was at least a strong military and secular authorities to keep these trends in check.\par \par \uc2 Now, the former is weakened while the latter is succumbing to Islamic populism in order to gain votes.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the police -- the guardians of law and order -- have a sinking credibility as they continue to be mired in one scandal after another.\par \par \uc2 This attitude of omission is further encouraging a sense of lawlessness on the streets. From laissez-faire to anything goes. Coupled by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  brought about by the supply of basic commodities and rising fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , expect Indonesian politics in 2011 to muddle through again.\par \par \uc2 Timeline 2010\par \par \uc2 o Feb. 2 The National Democrat organization under the auspices of breakaway Golkar politician Surya Paloh is declared.\par \par \uc2 o March. 2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  begins a plenary session to discuss findings on the \uc2 Bank Century\uc2  scandal.\par \par \uc2 o April 19 The Constitutional Court upholds the controversial Blasphemy Law.\par \par \uc2 o May 5 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani resigns.\par \par \uc2 o May 6 A Joint Secretariat (coalition) is established, headed by Golkar chairman Aburizal Bakrie.\par \par \uc2 o May 20 Agus Martowardojo is sworn in as finance minister.\par \par \uc2 o July 22 The US officially lifts its ban on the participation of the Indonesian Army's Special Forces (Kopassus) in joint Indonesia-US military activities.\par \par \uc2 o Sept. 24 Hendarman Supandji is honorably discharged from his post as attorney general by the President.\par \par \uc2 o Nov. 15 Gayus Tambunan admits in court that he went to Bali.\par \par \uc2 o Nov. 26 The President questions the validity of existing monarchies, thereby sparking a dispute over the sultanate of Yogyakarta.\par \par \uc2 o Dec. 16 Law No. 2/2008 on political parties is passed by the House.\par \par \uc2 The writer is editor-in-chief of The Jakarta Post.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101220e6ck0000p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
