\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesia rising in 2011\b0\par\par\uc2 1,348 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 21\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post    \par \par \uc2 Stefan Koeberle, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance during the global downturn stood out within the region.\par \par \uc2 In 2009, when activity in developing East Asia excluding China came to a standstill, Indonesia's growth slowed down, but remained at 4.5 percent, the third highest in the G20 after China and India.\par \par \uc2 Domestic consumption was supportive, aided by Indonesia's stable macro \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the strengthening of financial and corporate sector balance sheets over the previous decade. And the level and mix of Indonesia's exports also helped to insulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Growth in 2010 is likely to be close to 6 percent and, driven by similar growth patterns, along with rising investment, growth is expected to be at a similar level in 2011. Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position also contrasts with those countries hardest hit during the crisis, with \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt levels declining to below 30 percent of GDP and a relatively low \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2010.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, 2010 has not been without domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges. Weather-related shocks to food prices hit the inflation rate mid-year and more recently as domestic rice prices have risen. The impact of these shocks is particularly felt by the poor. Short-term foreign capital positions have also ebbed and recently flowed strongly, with May's outflows highlighting Indonesia's vulnerability to shocks to investor sentiment.\par \par \uc2 Over the near-term similar challenges will likely remain. Until the growth recovery in the G7 takes hold, monetary easing will contribute to the flow of liquidity towards emerging markets. The creditworthiness of emerging economies has risen relative to highly indebted higher income sovereigns.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, amidst the recent turmoil of the eurozone debt crisis, credit default swap spreads are already lower for Indonesia than many investment grade sovereigns with higher income levels. Benchmark reweightings to reflect these trends could stimulate a further rise in demand for assets in Indonesia from global institutional investors. Managing capital inflows will therefore remain a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  priority.\par \par \uc2 Patterns of global trade and capital flows, the structure of production networks underpinning these flows, and energy and commodity prices are all likely to be quite different in the post-crisis global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 And these \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  currents of the post-crisis world underlie the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for Indonesia in 2011, and beyond, in that they will determine the price of commodity exports and Indonesia's scope to enhance its exports of manufactured goods, as well as affect the government's cost of borrowing and the cost of capital for domestic firms.\par \par \uc2 In this post-crisis world, the shift in relative growth rates is likely to stimulate greater "South-South" trade and cross-border investment and a reweighting of exports away from manufactured products bound for G7 final demand. Commodity prices are expected to rise gradually associated with the growth of large emerging economies such as China and India.\par \par \uc2 Further opportunities may arise from China's rebalancing towards domestic services and private consumption and moves into higher value added production.\par \par \uc2 As global production networks adjust, this could open up a space and opportunities for regional economies such as Indonesia to integrate further within international supply chains and move further into labor-intensive manufacturing, helping to diversify the export mix.\par \par \uc2 Navigating these changing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  currents, Indonesia in 2011 has the opportunity to continue its rise as a dynamic, inclusive middle-income \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is fortunate to have multiple potential drivers of growth, including commodities, labor-intensive industry or developing a dynamic domestic services sector.\par \par \uc2 Meeting the vision of a rising Indonesia is about accelerating growth in a way that continues to bring about sustained and significant reductions in poverty and broad-based increases in income.\par \par \uc2 Achieving such inclusive growth requires the expansion of quality employment opportunites to the poor or near-poor and the provision of safety nets to those who are hit by adverse events affecting their health, purchasing power, or livelihoods.\par \par \uc2 To accelerate growth to the 7 percent-plus level that it has the potential to realize, Indonesia needs to invest more, particularly in critical areas like infrastructure but also in job-creating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.\par \par \uc2 These investments can be government-catalyzed and private sector-driven through the right \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  improvements for the investment climate and complementary \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  investments. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  space for such investments can be partly achieved through a reallocation of expenditures. This includes targeting energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  towards the poor and away from the wealthier segments that benefit most under the current system.\par \par \uc2 On the financing side, much of the needed additional investment can be domestically financed. But capital inflows, particularly Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) and longer-term portfolio investments, can play an important role, with the former having the additional benefits of potential technology transfers. There are two main areas wherein Indonesia could do more to attract job-creating investment.\par \par \uc2 The first is to reduce regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and ensure consistent implementation of regulations governing investment, especially FDI. There have been a number of instances in recent years where the laws, regulations and decrees governing foreign investment in particular sectors have been in conflict.\par \par \uc2 The issue is not so much the limits on foreign investment, though there is considerable scope to rationalize and streamline the licensing and regulatory requirements to make Indonesia a more attractive investment destination.\par \par \uc2 Rather, it is the lack of transparency and certainty about the investment \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  regime. Many governments limit foreign investment in particular sectors for specific reasons. But it is important to do so in a coherent, consistent and transparent manner and one which respects previous commitments.\par \par \uc2 The second is to enhance connectivity, within and between Indonesia's islands and internationally, by reducing transport and logistics costs. The priorities here are to reduce the cost of inter-island shipping by improving the efficiency of regional ports, provide stronger incentives for local governments to build and maintain their own infrastructure and complete back-bone infrastructure (such as the Trans-Java Expressway) to increase the access that the rural poor have to markets in Indonesia and elsewhere. To achieve these priorities, progress on issues like land-acquisition is critical, but even more so is the need for effective coordination across the multiple levels and parts of government.\par \par \uc2 The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  currents of trade and capital, commodities and production networks, are changing in the post-crisis world. Indonesia is also experiencing shifts in demographics and urbanization.\par \par \uc2 The challenge for 2011 is to harness these currents to realize the vision of a stronger and more stable Indonesia, to move towards an Indonesia which can accelerate its growth in a way that brings about sustained and significant reductions in poverty and broad-based increases in income.\par \par \uc2 Realizing this vision of a rising Indonesia will require persistent coordinated action on the part of the government and will often involve difficult \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  choices. If these choices are postponed, if the needed coordination is not enforced, and if Indonesia continues to rely solely on its natural strengths, it will miss a tremendous opportunity to rise into the ranks of the world's top dynamic and inclusive middle-income economies.\par \par \uc2 With Indonesia's increasingly prominent role in the global arena -- in 2011 it will assume Chairmanship of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, and continue to be a member of the G20 -- comes greater expectations and responsibilities.\par \par \uc2 This will be particularly true on the issue of climate change -- perhaps the biggest challenge of this generation -- where Indonesia has already carved out a place for itself on the global stage, including through President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's 2009 Copenhagen commitment to reduce emissions and avoid deforestation.\par \par \uc2 Concerted effort to progress on other domestic structural development challenges -- enhanced domestic connectivity, a more transparent and certain regulatory environment for investment, job creation and social protection -- will be equally important to realize the vision of a rising Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 The writer 