\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy \highlight\uc2 : Time to reduce interest payment costs\b0\par\par\uc2 1,140 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 24\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Helmi Arman, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In the midst of rapid capital inflows and improving perceptions on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  lies an opportunity to enhance the country's strategy on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  financing.\par \par \uc2 Capital inflows are likely to remain a very warm issue for next year. Given the unsustainable debt levels in the developed world, as well as the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth outlook thereat, emerging markets will continue to be a haven for cross-border investment and yield seeking.\par \par \uc2 In 2010, Indonesia saw breathtaking amounts of capital inflows. During the first three quarters of the year, for example, foreign direct investment and financial market capital inflows reached a record high US$23 billion (or around 3 percent of the size of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 Accordingly, the portion of local currency bonds owned by foreign investors continues to rise and, at around 30 percent, is currently the highest in the region.\par \par \uc2 Given Indonesia's shallow financial markets, there is obviously a scarcity of available local currency financial instruments, especially when it comes to the huge influx of foreign funds.\par \par \uc2 Of course, on one hand this condition leaves us prone to high levels of volatility, not to mention asset price bubbles. But on the brighter side, the scarcity of instruments also gives the government (as a key supplier of bonds) an upper-hand in the markets.\par \par \uc2 Bond yields are at historical lows and selling debt has become a much easier task. The government now has more freedom when it comes to issuing papers for financing the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This change in landscape is actually giving room for us to revisit the traditional paradigms in managing \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  finances.\par \par \uc2 Honestly, although debt management has seen many improvements in the way it is run, things haven't been exactly perfect.\par \par \uc2 At the end of every \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, a good portion of the funds raised from bond financing ends up unused.\par \par \uc2 At the end of 2008, for example, funds raised in excess of what was needed reached a staggering Rp 80 trillion. This was repeated in 2009 with Rp 40 trillion, and probably another significant amount this year.\par \par \uc2 Over-financing is very inefficient and wasteful, as taxpayers must pay a fortune to cover interest payments on an idle loan.\par \par \uc2 For example, the average yield on bonds issued in 2008 was around 11 percent per annum. We can easily calculate that from a principle of Rp 80 trillion, the redundant interest payments can potentially reach trillions annually, equaling the annual cost of putting hundreds of thousands of impoverished children through school.\par \par \uc2 This tendency to over-finance stems from many structural reasons; one is a chronic tendency to underachieve the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  target on infrastructure. To fix this requires addressing many structural problems, such as land acquisition, which could take some time.\par \par \uc2 However, what we can realistically aim for 2011, in regard to reducing the likeliness and cost of over-financing, is to add more flexibility to the financing side.\par \par \uc2 We can see the extent of over-financing all this time has been made worse by the government's debt management strategies to mitigate the so-called refinancing risk; i.e. the possibility of being unable to borrow and repay existing debt.\par \par \uc2 The refinancing risk was indeed a big issue five or 10 years ago in the years of recovery from the 1998 financial crisis. In order to reduce this refinancing risk, the government's rule of thumb on debt management has been to issue bonds with a maturity of as long as possible, as soon as possible.\par \par \uc2 Under the so-called strategy of "frontloading", huge amounts of debt are sold in the early months of every year. Longer tenor bond issuances have also become a high priority over shorter tenor bonds.\par \par \uc2 The average maturity of the government's bond portfolio has been maintained at around eight years, which looks high even at regional standards.\par \par \uc2 According to data from the Asian Development Bank, peer countries such as China, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand all have more outstanding short-tenor debt (one to three years) than they do long-tenor debt (more than 10 years). Only in Indonesia does the reverse apply.\par \par \uc2 Of course, this doesn't mean we must follow everything the others do. But considering Indonesia's chronic and wasteful excess financing problem, continuously prioritizing the sale of long-term bonds increasingly looks like a costly strategy.\par \par \uc2 It's high time for this to change. The government should, first, reconsider its strategy of frontloading and second, start using more short tenor bills (that mature within the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year) to minimize interest payments.\par \par \uc2 A lot has changed since 2005. The refinancing risk should no longer be the major concern as Indonesia's fundamentals have improved, and investment grade status is within a couple of years' reach. All this is leading to an era of easier access to financing.\par \par \uc2 Generally, the government should no longer be too concerned about the prospect of being locked out of the markets and unable to fund the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In this regard, the additional cost incurred from issuing long tenor instead of short tenor is starting to look less justifiable. Given the current shape of the yield curve, issuing a one-year bill in place of a 20-year bond can reduce the annual interest payment by a staggering 3 percentage points.\par \par \uc2 The issuance of more short-term T-bills should also be taken in the context of deepening the market. Local banks have hundreds of trillions in excess liquidity that the government could tap into. Cooperation with \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  in using T-bills as a monetary instrument (which has stalled for years) should again be restarted.\par \par \uc2 The government can even go further to introduce very short tenor T-bills, with a maturity of less than a year, for bridging the seasonal financing gaps that stem from time differences in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and revenue collection.\par \par \uc2 For example, issuing one- and three-month T-bills instead of long-term bonds to bridge the early-year cash shortage would likely be much more efficient. Not only are T-bills cheaper in cost, they could also be timed to mature in April when money from \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection fills up the government's coffers. This way the chances of paying excessive interest on idle money just might be significantly reduced.\par \par \uc2 The prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies in which the government has held dear for so long are finally bearing fruit. The opportunity has risen to put things further to our advantage. Now is the time to take it.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at Bank Danamon Indonesia. The views expressed herein are personal.\par \par \uc2 photo caption\par \par \uc2 JP/R. Berto Wedhatama\par \par \uc2 Banking on space: The banking industry continues to grow, leaving behind the Asian financial crisis of the late 1990s and the American-led financial crisis in 2008 and 2009.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101220e6ck0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Expansion Phase Until 2016;  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  to Spur Next Year\b0\par\par\uc2 812 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 December 2010\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year is estimated to surge, thanks to stronger global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook caused by the current business cycle expansion phase.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee (KEN) Chairul Tanjung revealed historic data showed Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  usually could expand for an average of seven years. Indonesia entered its expansion phase in March 2009.\par \par \uc2 "So, Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still have its expansion phase until 2016," he informed at a discussion titled Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook 2011 in Jakarta yesterday.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year, he added, was estimated at 6.4%, with total \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  output reaching IDR7,726 trillion (around US$858.4 billion), thanks to better global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook.\par \par \uc2 The KEN forecasts consumption, investment, and export will still drive Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year, creating a more balanced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth engine.\par \par \uc2 Household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is predicted to increase by 5%, government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  by 15.5%, and investment (gross fixed capital formation) by 13.4%.\par \par \uc2 "Moreover, the improved global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2010 has significantly bolstered our export performance. Next year, export is estimated to grow by 13%," he said.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Federation of Private Domestic Banks (Perbanas) Sigit Pramono revealed the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth potential next year had to be exploited optimally to boost prioritized \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors.\par \par \uc2 "The government, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI), the banking industry, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  players have to sit together to reach a consensus on which \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors should be prioritized."\par \par \uc2 The sectors, continued Sigit, would receive abundant financing, thanks to the anticipated capital inflow and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2011.\par \par \uc2 "If we can boost all sectors, it will be good. Or at least we should have leading industries to prioritize," he said.\par \par \uc2 Sigit inserted all parties should also play their respective role in boosting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors by issuing relevant policies and regulations.\par \par \uc2 "The government should play its role in making \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , custom and excise policies, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  should play its role in making monetary policies, and the banking industry should also play its respective role."\par \par \uc2 However, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growths this year and next year are predicted not to be as high as expected, hitting even lower points than other developing countries. This is the conclusion of a focus group discussion held by some economists at the Indonesian Economists Association (ISEI).\par \par \uc2 Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is only estimated to grow 5,9% this year and 6%-6.4% next year.\par \par \uc2 Secretary General of the ISEI Anggito Abimanyu disclosed floor \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth limit was fixed at 6% since the investment sector had not yet improved.\par \par \uc2 "If we want to see our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth surging, sources of investment have to increase. During the discussion, some were still of opinion that Indonesia had not yet found its investment sector improved."\par \par \uc2 Moreover, he inserted, the declining global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth forecast would also affect Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year. "Consumption will remain the main driver. However, export will also be steady, thanks to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery."\par \par \uc2 Potential instability\par \par \uc2 Sri Adiningsih, a member of ISEI from Gadjah Mada University, viewed the potential of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  instability or vulnerability next year would be higher than this year. Global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment next year would not be as good as this year, making it difficult for Indonesia to maintain domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability.\par \par \uc2 "Competition to attract global investments will be more difficult since China will issue more bonds and shares, thus, boosting risk threat," she said.\par \par \uc2 She further told that the potential to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year would not be significant since there would be no essential global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2011.\par \par \uc2 Export growth was estimated to decline and so would commodity prices. "Therefore, Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2011 will grow, but not significant," cited Adiningsih.\par \par \uc2 Didik J. Rachbini, another member of the ISEI, added Indonesia was not able to optimally take advantage of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and soaring commodity price momentums in 2010 due to the government's unfavorable policies.\par \par \uc2 "Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will slightly increase next year. This is not optimal since we actually have the momentum. Unfortunately, the factors of state bureaucracy, political process, and political market have not been favorable," he explained.\par \par \uc2 The ISEI estimates \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for 2010 at 5.9%, year-on-year inflation at 6.5%, and the rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar at IDR9,000.\par \par \uc2 For 2011, the ISEI projects \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth at 6%-6,4%, and inflation at 6.2%-6.7% due to government policies on the food sector, especially on rice, and on \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  base electricity tariffs and fuel prices.\par \par \uc2 The rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar is estimated at IDR8,900-IDR9,100, \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at 1.5% of GDP, foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  at US$104 billion-US$109 billion, the benchmark BI Rate at 6.5%-6.75%, and the Composite Stock Index (IHSG) at 4,200. (Bisnis/14/20/aca/gps)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020101221e6cl0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
