\par\par \b \uc2 Living with inflation, capital inflows, poor infrastructure\b0\par\par\uc2 1,092 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 December 2010\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2010 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Vincent Lingga, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The biggest \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges for the Indonesian government in the year ahead include how to cope with rising inflationary pressures, ensure less volatile and sustainable capital inflows and accelerate the development of infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Certainly, the large role portfolio investment plays in total capital inflows and the ensuing risks of asset price bubbles pose challenges for controlling inflation, especially in case of sudden capital reversals.\par \par \uc2 The year may end with a cumulative inflation of at least 6.2 percent, much higher than last year's 2.78 percent. But this would not prompt the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to immediately raise its benchmark interest rate, which has remained at 6.5 percent since August 2009, because the rise in food prices, caused by weather anomalies that reduced supplies, was the main driver behind the increase in the consumer price index.\par \par \uc2 The reluctance to hike \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , at least until the end of the first quarter, also stems from great concern that a further widening of interest rate differentials would attract more short-term capital inflows, further complicating the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's liquidity management efforts.\par \par \uc2 But the risks to the inflation outlook have increased due to the combination of persistently strong domestic demand, supply disruptions caused by weather anomalies and inflationary pressures due to capacity constraints and inefficient logistics.\par \par \uc2 The government measure to gradually phase out fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  starting in April will also aggravate inflationary pressures next year.\par \par \uc2 The growth of gross domestic product in the third quarter surprised on the downside, coming in at 5.8 percent year-on-year, down from 6.2 percent in the second quarter due to the unusually wet weather which adversely affected mining, construction and exports.\par \par \uc2 But, persistently high domestic consumer confidence will still enable the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to close this year with a minimum expansion of 6 percent.\par \par \uc2 Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will remain the main driver of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which is estimated at between 6.3 and 6.5 percent next year, due in part to the positive wealth effect from the stock market andrising wages.\par \par \uc2 "\par \par \uc2 Since infrastructure development consists mostly of multi-year projects, the highest growth the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may achieve next year is 6.5 percent. A faster expansion may cause the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to burst at the seams.\par \par \uc2 "\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue the use of a mix of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and macro-prudential measures to deal with inflation risk, strong capital inflows and high excess onshore liquidity by setting higher compulsory reserve requirements, including on dollar deposits, and regulating vostro accounts (rupiah demand deposit accounts held by non-residents in domestic banks).\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will use more liquidity management tools rather than the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate. Hence, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's first line of defense will continue to be liquidity withdrawal by raising the dollar reserve requirement and further lengthening the maturity of the term deposit facility to lock in additional liquidity for longer durations.\par \par \uc2 The 6.25 percentage point interest rate differential, and substantial improvements in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals, will continue to be magnets of both foreign direct and portfolio investment to the country.\par \par \uc2 According to the International Monetary Fund in Jakarta, foreign direct investment in the first nine months of 2010 alone totaled US$6.77 billion, compared to a mere $1.92 billion in all of 2009, while portfolio capital reached $14.45 billion against $10.36 billion last year.\par \par \uc2 Most portfolio capital inflows this year went to buying government bonds ($10 billion), \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's SBI debt papers ($2.37 billion) and shares ($2.1 billion) as of early October.\par \par \uc2 Certainly, the best approach to cope with the torrent of short-term capital inflows, and to gain the greatest benefit from them, is to convert the funds into direct investment and initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings (IPO) through the stock exchange and lengthen the maturity of capital inflows, thereby reducing the volatility.\par \par \uc2 But this requires significant improvement in the overall investment climate, reducing infrastructure bottlenecks and further improving capital market infrastructure to encourage more IPOs and corporate bond issuance.\par \par \uc2 Inadequate infrastructure has been one of the biggest drags on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion over the past few years. In fact, the country lags behind most major Southeast Asian economies in the adequacy and quality of infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Lack of inter-connectivity between major islands has caused wide regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disparities.\par \par \uc2 Infrastructure, such as roads and port facilities, in many provinces has crumbled due to an acute lack of maintenance under severe \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  restraints. Power shortages and rotating blackouts continue to hit several provinces.\par \par \uc2 Inadequate infrastructure impairs the competitiveness of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because production and distribution costs are made much higher than those in other countries.\par \par \uc2 Studies by the University of Indonesia School of Economics concluded that inadequate infrastructure and the crumbling condition of existing infrastructure have made the costs of logistics in the country among the highest in Asia, or 14 percent of total production costs, compared to four to five percent in other countries.\par \par \uc2 The biggest barrier to private investment in infrastructure is land acquisition. The arduous, complex procedures for land acquisition make this component the biggest factor of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for project cost.\par \par \uc2 Yet more discouraging is that the government is still drafting a law on land acquisition for infrastructure that should have been completed early this year.\par \par \uc2 The most optimistic view now is that the bill would be enacted in the first half of 2011, at the soonest. However, because the new law has yet to be supported with government regulations stipulating technical details for its enforcement, more investor-friendly land acquisition \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  can be expected only later next year, or even early 2012.\par \par \uc2 The government has set up several supporting facilities to help expedite infrastructure financing, such as the infrastructure finance company in a joint venture with the World Bank and Asian Development Bank and an infrastructure fund guarantee.\par \par \uc2 But don't expect any substantial improvement in the infrastructure sector unless a strong regulatory framework for a more expeditious land acquisition system is already in place.\par \par \uc2 The government built only about 120 kilometers of toll roads over the past five years and completed even less than 40 percent of the 10,000 megawatts in new power generation capacity launched under a crash program in early 2006 to cope with the power crisis.\par \par \uc2 Since infrastructure development consists mostly of multi-year projects, the highest growth the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may achieve next year is 6.5 percent. A faster expansion may cause the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to burst at the seams.\par \par \uc2 The author is a staff writer at The Jakarta Post.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020101221e6cl0000t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
