\par\par \b \uc2 Coal production expected to exceed 340m tons this year\b0\par\par\uc2 Rangga D. Fadillah, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 495 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 To catch up with growing domestic and international market demand, Indonesian coal miners expect to produce 340 million tons of coal this year, an increase of 23 percent from 275 million tons in 2010.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Coal Mining Association (APBI) executive director Supriatna Suhala said that almost all coal miners in the country had expressed their commitments to expanding production in 2011.\par \par \uc2 "As the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovers, we expect to see growing demand for coal, both at domestic and international markets next year [2011]," he told The Jakarta Post over the weekend.\par \par \uc2 Of the planned 340 million tons to be produced in 2011, the association estimates that 20 percent -- around 70 million tons -- will be allocated to fulfill domestic market demand, while the remaining 80 percent would be exported.\par \par \uc2 "We predict soaring demand for coal in emerging market countries, particularly to supply their energy sectors," Supriatna said, adding that Japan, India, China and South Korea would remain the largest importers of Indonesian coal.\par \par \uc2 According to the Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry, Indonesia's coal production reached 275 million tons in 2010. However, APBI's calculation resulted in a different figure. The association claims that the production may have actually hit 300 million tons because the government does not record output from many small-scale miners in several provinces.\par \par \uc2 The government should work hand in hand with Indonesia's miners to achieve the target of producing 340 million tons of coal this year, Supriatna said. The most crucial point the government needed to pay attention to was infrastructure development, he added.\par \par \uc2 "We badly need more roads to connect mining sites and ports. Access is currently very difficult because some regional administrations prohibit heavy equipment to pass through \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  roads," he said.\par \par \uc2 Supriatna suggested that if the government really supported the plan to expand coal production, it should increase efforts to invite private investors to get involved in the country's infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 "In the first half of this year [2010], coal production was very high, but then slowed down in the second half due to the extreme rainy season," Supriatna said, adding that heavy rains had disrupted coal delivery processes across the country.\par \par \uc2 Besides infrastructure, miners also demanded the government develop down-stream coal industries. The Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry is now preparing a ministerial decree on detailed strategies and guidelines to develop downstream mining industries. The government is fully committed to utilizing local resources in developing down-stream industries.\par \par \uc2 Supriatna hoped that the central government could improve coordination with regional administrations to prevent legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by inconsistent implementation of laws at the regional level.\par \par \uc2 According to the ministry's mineral and coal directorate general, in December 2010 the coal reference price (HBA) stood at US$103.41 per ton. APBI predicts that the price will stay above $100 in 2011, in line with the projected increase in demand.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110103e7130001d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
