\par\par \b \uc2 The threat of global inflation\b0\par\par\uc2 1,055 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 January 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The threat of high inflation is now looming large on the horizon not only for Indonesia but also for other countries. After being hit by a most severe recession in 2008-2009, the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is now already on the path to recovery, although the pace of that recovery differs from country to country.\par \par \uc2 The damages caused by the global financial crisis have not been entirely repaired, but there is growing confidence among policymakers, businesses and consumers that the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is regaining its feet, albeit slowly.\par \par \uc2 The mending of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not fully complete, yet many countries have to deal with another threat: The re-emergence of an inflationary spiral, which if not dealt with promptly and correctly, could produce more painful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social impacts.\par \par \uc2 During the 1970s, the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was gripped by high inflation after oil prices quadrupled in the aftermath of the war in the Middle East and the Iranian revolution. Inflation ran at double-digit levels in many countries.\par \par \uc2 For the developed countries, double digit inflation was something unprecedented since World War II.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses by the developed countries were too harsh, pushing the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into recession and stagnation.\par \par \uc2 The world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was faced with a new kind of phenomenon called "stagflation", a situation where \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stagnation runs in concurrence with high inflation.\par \par \uc2 But for the last two decades inflation rates have come down substantially. In the US inflation dropped from 15 percent in 1980 to 3-4 percent since 2000.\par \par \uc2 In the developing countries, inflation averaged 50 percent annually in 1989-1998. By 2006, inflation was 5 percent. This has brought \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability in the world, producing sustained \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, higher income and prosperity.\par \par \uc2 During this period most countries only experienced mild inflation, and the incidence of double-digit inflation -- previously the hallmark of many developing countries -- was very rare.\par \par \uc2 The only exception was probably in Zimbabwe, where the inflation rate hit 1,000 percent recently at the peak of its political crisis.\par \par \uc2 Economists attributed the decline in global inflation to two significant forces: the fall of trade barriers and the fall of the Berlin wall.\par \par \uc2 As free trade was adopted by more and more countries, trade barriers -- both \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  and non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- fell all over the world, bringing down the price of goods and services.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, rapid technological developments in transport and communications in the last decade helped drive down the cost of transportation of goods and services.\par \par \uc2 The fall of the Berlin wall in the late 1980s accelerated the downfall of the Soviet Union, giving birth to several new states. Millions of people from these new countries emigrated to Western Europe and the United States.\par \par \uc2 These immigrants flooded the labor market, bringing down labor costs in those countries. But the impact of these two great developments on inflation is declining, as the move to further free trade is facing many hurdles and the influx of migration from the former Soviet republic subsided. Forces that hold down inflationary pressures are losing their strength.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, as the impacts of the financial crisis drove the threat of inflation far away, the concerns of the impacted countries turned to how to avert deflation. At this stage, deflation is perceived as a threat that contains more perils than inflation.\par \par \uc2 The experience of Japan provided painful lessons on how hard it is for an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to get back on its feet once it has been strangled by deflation. No country wants to suffer the lost decade that Japan endured.\par \par \uc2 But \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses by the developed economies during the recent crisis have planted the seeds of inflationary pressures.\par \par \uc2 Huge liquidity that has been pumped into the financial system, coupled with \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits, would be inflationary, once \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery takes hold. Higher commodity prices would exacerbate these inflationary pressures.\par \par \uc2 The price of oil price is nearing US$100 per barrel, and in the short-term there seems to be no force that can reverse the trend.\par \par \uc2 Emerging economies have also started experiencing inflationary pressures. Unlike developed economies where overly loose monetary conditions set the stage for inflationary pressures, in emerging economies inflation is more the result of rises of food and commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 As more and more people in these countries enjoy higher standards of living, their demand for food escalates and becomes more varied, pushing upward pressure on food prices. Unfortunately, the increase in food production lags behind the growing demand.\par \par \uc2 Worse, food production has been subject to disruptions from weather anomalies. Drought, dry weather, and floods have either delayed or damaged grain harvest in the US, Russia, Australia and other grain producing countries.\par \par \uc2 The price of rice, wheat, corn and edible oils have surged by 50 percent in recent months. Whether this weather related supply disruption is temporary or not, nobody can predict.\par \par \uc2 But the surge in demand for foods would stretch the available supply to its limit, and it would take some time to fix it.\par \par \uc2 So all signs indicate that a reemergence of inflation is imminent.\par \par \uc2 The era of declining global inflation is coming to an end. For the middle class this price surge has little impact on their cost of living. But for millions of poor people who live on US$1 or $2 a day, and who have to spend two thirds or more of their income on foods the impact would be devastating.\par \par \uc2 The response of policymakers to these impending inflationary pressures has been varied. China and India have employed a pre-emptive strike method by raising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  early on to staunch the inflationary threat.\par \par \uc2 The market has been given firm signals from the authorities in their resolve to contain inflation, thus ending \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , prefers to use a more cautionary approach, by delaying any interest rate increase on the grounds that core inflation is still within the tolerable limits. It has used a non-interest \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , by absorbing excess liquidity.\par \par \uc2 For the policymakers the immediate question is whether tightening monetary policies would be the appropriate response for the kind of inflation that is caused by supply shocks and disruptions.\par \par \uc2 Tightening monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could stem inflationary expectations, but the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown that would result would also hurt the poor more than others.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110112e71c0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
