\par\par \b \uc2 Editorial: Vulnerable food situation\b0\par\par\uc2 634 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 January 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 The vulnerable food situation we are now facing is similar to that in the energy sector. Decades of misguided energy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and hugely wasteful \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  have made the nation dependent mostly on fossil fuels despite the availability of other energy sources such as geothermal, coal and solar power.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, the steep price hikes in rice prices since the last quarter of 2010 have again rudely awakened the government to the need to redesign the concept of its food security which has thus far wrongly focused on adequate supply of rice at affordable prices for all people at all times.\par \par \uc2 We find it mind-boggling as to why the government has stubbornly refused to accept the blunt fact that it is impossible for such a vast archipelago country of more than 237 million people with an annual national consumption of 33 million tons of rice -- which keeps increasing - to sustain rice self-sufficiency.\par \par \uc2 Consumption is steady throughout the year while rice harvests come only twice a year in Java and for the most part once a year on the other islands, which do not have sufficient irrigation networks.\par \par \uc2 Now the government comes up again with a pathetic response, talking about contingency measures to increase rice buffer stocks and improve price-stabilization through stock management by the \uc2 National Logistics Agency\uc2  and implement food crop diversification.\par \par \uc2 But we are afraid it will soon be back to business as usual as soon as international food prices begin to fall again.\par \par \uc2 If that is the case, we are in for a bigger risk of a food crisis because most analysts have projected the steep food price hikes which began late last year will accelerate due to supply disruptions caused by weather anomalies and steady rising demand in emerging and populous countries such as China, India and Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Analysts agree that the present upward price trend will likely be a permanent development due to the cascading impact of the climate \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , steady rise in demand, high oil prices that make fertilizer much dearer, and farm-land conversion into other industrial uses.\par \par \uc2 Like oil, the era of cheap food has ended. We should be aware that energy and food shortages are the biggest threat to our national stability in the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors.\par \par \uc2 The FAO food-price index, which rose for the sixth consecutive month by 4.3 percent in December, driven by sugar and cereals, is projected to continue to rise.\par \par \uc2 Poor weather conditions in major exporting countries across the globe have significantly curtailed harvests and expectations, sending prices sharply higher. Corn and wheat futures have both increased by 50 percent since the end of 2009, and soybeans are up 33 percent.\par \par \uc2 We share the concern raised by Franciscus Welirang, the chief executive officer of PT Bogasari, the country's largest wheat-flour producer, at the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting here early this week that we are already in a food crisis that could be worse than that of early 2008.\par \par \uc2 In the absence of new technology breakthroughs and any significant expansion in rice acreage outside Java due to the lack of irrigation networks, the best \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  option is to step up food crop diversification programs through an integrated agricultural development concept.\par \par \uc2 Food security should be made part of a broad-based agriculture development program with the ultimate objective of increasing rural household incomes both from farm and off-farm activities.\par \par \uc2 It is much better to invest the billions of dollars currently wasted annually on fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  in farm and rural infrastructure to enable farmers to diversify their rice crops to higher-value horticulture, fruits and other secondary food crops.\par \par \uc2 Of utmost importance is to consistently implement the integrated agricultural development program irrespective of the volatility of food commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110114e71e0000s\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
