\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Will 2011 be just another 2010?\b0\par\par\uc2 795 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 January 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Bahtiar Effendy, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Certainly there is a lot to be thankful for as we leave 2010 safely behind as there was not any major turmoil -- socio-economically or politically. Aware of the rough early months of President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's new administration, we were not quite certain what 2010 would bring. Indeed, there was a lot of apprehension about what stood before us throughout the year.\par \par \uc2 Actually, the newly formed government was off to a good start. Early in November of 2009, the so-called National Summit was held in Jakarta, bringing together almost 1,000 businessmen, economists andgovernment officials to put into effect what Yudhoyono had wanted all along: To generate growth in order to alleviate poverty and reduce unemployment.\par \par \uc2 It all started with the "Gecko versus Crocodile" case. This was a tacit rivalry between two agencies responsible for combating corruption: the Corruption Eradication Commission (KPK) and the National Police. Late in 2009, the rivalry culminated in the latter's alleged attempt to "criminalize" the former, with two of its leading figures, Chandra M. Hamzah and Bibit Samad Rianto, the scapegoats. The release of a recorded conversation played at the Constitutional Court served as an important indicator regarding the matter.\par \par \uc2 That was then followed by the \uc2 Bank Century\uc2  scandal, involving not only a substantial amount of state money (Rp 6.76 trillion or US$716 million) but also implicating the very core of President Yudhoyono's Cabinet, most notably Vice President Boediono and former finance minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati. A special committee was formed by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  to look into the affair. After several months of hard work, the House in a vote concluded that the decision to bail out \uc2 Bank Century\uc2  was wrong, and there were indeed irregularities in the bailout decision and its implementation.\par \par \uc2 Nothing was actually done to follow up on the decision. But, the Yudhoyono government had to bear the burden. That included the involuntary resignation of Sri Mulyani and the formation of a coalition joint secretariat with the day-to-day leadership given to Aburizal Bakrie -- chair of the second-largest political party (Golkar) and a presidential hopeful in 2014.\par \par \uc2 Given the nature of Indonesia's system of government, this joint secretariat actually has no bearing whatsoever on how the President runs his Cabinet or how he formulates and implements policies.\par \par \uc2 Symbolically, however, it represented Yudhoyono's defeat as he had to grant concessions to his coalition partners, especially Aburizal and Golkar.\par \par \uc2 So, by mid 2010, Golkar was able to turn the fiasco into an advantage for the party. Other members of the coalition were not as fortunate as Golkar. This was precisely where the points of contention among the coalition partners originated. Under these circumstances it was difficult for Yudhoyono to push his agenda through. Practically, he was shackled by power politicking. Instead of helping to govern, the coalition partnership hampered Yudhoyono's endeavors to realize his programs.\par \par \uc2 This unproductive state of power politics was made worse by several unresolved problems: weak law enforcement; corrupt law enforcers and bureaucrats; questions about the legality of the attorney general raised by former minister and state secretary Yusril Ihza Mahendra; the seemingly endless natural disasters including floods in Papua, a tsunami and earthquake in West Sumatra and Mount Merapi's volcanic eruptions in Central Java; the diplomatic hiccups that embarrassed Indonesia in the canceling of President Yudhoyono's trip to the Netherlands; and many others.\par \par \uc2 Put in the context of the above political and environmental realities, I am not so sure President Yudhoyono can smile as wide as he was when he left 2010 behind. Perhaps, he is also as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  as many others about what 2011 will bring. The scandalous Gayus H. Tambunan \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  mafia case, which represents a microcosm of the debilitating state of Indonesia's political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  morality, could actually remedy the long-standing ill reputation of the government.\par \par \uc2 This could occur only if the government, through its law enforcement agencies under the direct leadership of President Yudhoyono, was willing to tackle the serious issues. Running the government as business as usual, as if 2010 was still here, would only irritate the many religious leaders who have claimed that President Yudhoyono's government has been lying all along. The fact that Gayus' much discussed legal and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evasion issues ended with a verdict of only seven years in prison plus a Rp 300 million fine will certainly engender further distrust of the government.\par \par \uc2 From what has been presented, it is clear that unless and until the government gets its act together, the turbulent specter of 2010 will continue to haunt.\par \par \uc2 The writer is dean at the School of Social and Political Science at State Islamic University, Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110126e71q00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
