\par\par \b \uc2 Funds that leave a lasting legacy\b0\par\par\uc2 972 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 January 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 15\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post    \par \par \uc2 Nuno Fernandes,\par \par \uc2 Sovereign Wealth Funds (SWFs) have been making headlines around the world during the global financial crisis. Investors are noting their potential global impact and the effect that they can have on investment strategies at a time when lack of confidence in the financial markets has driven many investors and funds away from corporations.\par \par \uc2 They are also becoming increasingly prominent thanks to some huge investments -- tens of billions of dollars -- into major Western financial institutions, including \uc2 UBS\uc2  and \uc2 Merrill Lynch\uc2 , as well as less-familiar companies such as Madame Tussauds and MGM Casinos.\par \par \uc2 Some analysts predict that SWFs will manage more than US$10,000 billion within the next five years -- five times that controlled by the private equity and hedge fund markets combined.\par \par \uc2 A different sort of fund\par \par \uc2 Although exact definitions vary, SWFs are essentially state-owned funds that invest in international markets. They hold positions -- although rarely controlling stakes -- in nearly 20 percent of companies worldwide and operate in nearly every country in the developed world, as well as in a handful of emerging economies.\par \par \uc2 But what makes SWFs so different from other funds is that they consistently take a long-term investment view, because their underlying aim is to leave a legacy for future generations.\par \par \uc2 This approach is in sharp contrast to that of hedge funds, mutual funds and so forth, which tend to take a short-term perspective: How much money can I make this year? Am I going to beat the index?\par \par \uc2 This long-term investment approach also means that SWFs have great potential for assisting and shaping developmental change. Indeed, we are already seeing SWFs playing a more prominent role in social development.\par \par \uc2 In the Middle East, for example, many SWFs now see themselves as social development funds.\par \par \uc2 This might mean inviting the companies in which they invest to market their products in the home market, or influencing decisions about where to site off-shore production facilities.\par \par \uc2 Mubadala, a fund in Abu Dhabi that invested 8.1 percent into US computer chip maker AMD, is a good example of an SWF acting in this manner.\par \par \uc2 It has parlayed its involvement with AMD into a 20 percent stake and a profitable spin-off of its manufacturing operations, via a joint venture with the \uc2 Advanced Technology Investment Company\uc2  of Abu Dhabi.\par \par \uc2 It noted in its annual report that it was playing a role in the social development of Abu Dhabi -- something that fits very well with the state's overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development objectives, which prioritize the creation of full-scale sustainable businesses.\par \par \uc2 The benefits of SWF ownership\par \par \uc2 SWF investment has a considerable impact on company value: when an SWF invests in a company, the value of the company increases by 15 percent.\par \par \uc2 This suggests that general shareholders benefit -- a lot -- from SWFs investing in their companies. Furthermore, the impact of SWFs goes beyond that of the typical institutional investor, as the market usually pays a much higher premium for businesses in which SWFs have a stake than in organizations that are owned by general institutional investors. All else being equal, the market prefers SWFs to any other institutional investor.\par \par \uc2 And this is not just a market phenomenon. Companies with SWF investment also outperform other companies when measured on actual performance -- profit margins, return on assets, return on equity, and so forth. This shows that the higher valuations results are not an irrational market aberration.\par \par \uc2 SWFs add value in three main areas. First is the cost of capital. Firms that have sovereign wealth funds as investors have lower cost of capital than other firms.\par \par \uc2 That is traditional investment theory; when you have a lower cost of capital you will be able to take more investment projects and pursue more growth opportunities -- and that is appreciated in the market.\par \par \uc2 Related to this is capital stability. Once firms have an SWF as an investor, they have better access to capital should they need more in the future.\par \par \uc2 Unlike other types of institutional investors, SWFs typically provide guaranteed capital in case of future funding needs, thus reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the company's future financing ability.\par \par \uc2 The second benefit is an expanded product market: companies that have an SWF investor will also get privileged access to the product market in the country or region in which the fund is based.\par \par \uc2 The third is related to the takeover market and corporate governance. SWFs can save companies from hostile takeovers or corporate raiders. Their long-term investment approach and associated legacy and development objectives play an important part here because they avoid strategies that pursue short-term value at the cost of destroying consolidation or scale.\par \par \uc2 Unlike most other investors, they are willing to block value-reducing acquisitions in the companies in which they invest.\par \par \uc2 Here to stay\par \par \uc2 SWFs may only have come to the forefront of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  attention during the recent global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis but there is no doubt that they will become increasingly important part in the world's markets.\par \par \uc2 They will continue to invest and they will maintain their involvement in local development, thanks to their vision of achieving long-term financial and strategic returns from their investments for their home countries and regions.\par \par \uc2 This commitment and strength can be a powerful source of value creation for any company that has a SWF as an investor.\par \par \uc2 Markets have not seen investors like this before because the vast majority are short-term oriented. Sovereign wealth funds are very different.\par \par \uc2 They are stable investors that want to stay for the long term. This is a new and very good source of capital for corporations that we have not seen before.\par \par \uc2 Nuno Fernandes is professor of finance at IMD ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.imd.ch"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.imd.ch}}}\uc2 ), the leading global business school based in Lausanne, Switzerland. He directs IMD's Strategic Finance program.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110129e71t0001g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
