\par\par \b \uc2 CPI surges, putting more pressure on BI to up rate\b0\par\par\uc2 Esther Samboh, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 570 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 February 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The sharp increase in the inflation rate in January, largely caused by the soaring prices of chili and other food items, may force the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to finally increase its benchmark interest rate, which has now been kept at a record low level for a year and a half.\par \par \uc2 The Central Statistics Agency (BPS) announced on Tuesday that month-on-month inflation rose 0.89 percent in January largely due to soaring chili and rice prices.\par \par \uc2 The surge pushed headline inflation up to 7.02 percent on a year-on-year basis in January from 6.96 percent in December. BPS said, however, that core inflation slowed to 4.18 percent from 4.28 percent last month.\par \par \uc2 January inflation, for example, saw food prices contributing 0.57 percentage points to the overall 0.89 percent headline Composite Price Index (CPI), with chili prices accounting for 0.11 percentage points and rice prices adding another 0.11 percentage points.\par \par \uc2 "Chili prices have been extraordinary. They're literally hot," BPS chairman Rusman Heriawan told reporters at his office in Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 According to the BPS chairman, challenging moments for the country's inflation will be seen from February to April, when Indonesia usually records price deflation. "If inflation is seen during the period, there's no guarantee that the government's target of 5.3 percent growth this year could be met," he said, referring to the 2011 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimate.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) has kept its benchmark interest rate at record low of 6.5 percent since August, 2009 to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Darmin Nasution said last month the interest rate remained relevant given that the spike in inflation was mainly caused by volatile foods prices.\par \par \uc2 Darmin said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would raise the key interest rate only if core inflation -- a price index which excludes food and energy prices -- reached 5 percent.\par \par \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2  analyst Sin Beng Ong said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would unlikely increase its benchmark rate during the upcoming meeting on Friday because the surge in the January inflation was caused by increasing food prices. "Food prices are beyond the influence of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and non-food prices have been generally benign," he said.\par \par \uc2 However, several other analysts think differently. Gundy Cahyadi of \uc2 OCBC Bank\uc2  and Johanna Chua from Citibank considered a rate hike imminent given the mounting inflationary pressures.\par \par \uc2 "We believe BI will tilt toward hiking by 25 basis points on Friday to safeguard credibility amid the likely persistence of headline inflation beyond their target, the rising risks this feeds into core, the sharp sell-off in bond markets amid growing inflation worries and the hikes or hawkishness of neighboring central banks," Chua said in a statement.\par \par \uc2 But policymakers at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as well as the government, have expressed that it will not be easy to curb inflation with pressures coming from weather-related factors that have resulted in soaring food prices both at home and other parts of the world.\par \par \uc2 Analysts have forecast inflation peaking in April when the government's plan to remove the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for private cars in the Greater Jakarta is 