\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Indonesia: Fuelling up\b0\par\par\uc2 1,059 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Josh Franken , Oxford Business Group,\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's energy industry is looking to ramp up investments at home and abroad to boost output and help meet the growing demand from the domestic market while maintaining its position as a leading natural gas exporter.\par \par \uc2 In late January, state oil firm \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  announced it was embarking on a large-scale expansion program, with plans to spend up to US$1 billion on acquisitions. According to Frederick Siahaan, \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 's investment planning and risk management director, the company was casting its net wide when looking at possible acquisitions, with up to 20 assets across Asia and Africa in its sights.\par \par \uc2 "Many oil and gas blocks in Africa and the Caspian Sea are being offered to investors," he said while taking part in a trade convention in Jakarta on Jan. 25. "Several blocks with huge oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Kazakhstan are also on the list. We're still evaluating the possibility of going ahead with overseas acquisitions."\par \par \uc2 Along with a number of overseas fields that the company was hoping to buy in the coming year, \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  was also planning to acquire several domestic blocks, Siahaan said, part of a longer-term scheme to increase production to 1 million barrels of oil equivalent per day (boepd) by 2015 from the present rate of 420,000 boepd.\par \par \uc2 While there was no guarantee that \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  would win any or all of the bids for the overseas blocks, Frederick said that it was important for the firm to take part in the process and be more aggressive in expanding its business.\par \par \uc2 To fund this \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  is planning to tap into capital markets, issuing up to $2 billion worth of bonds and staging an initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offering for a 20-30 percent stake in its insurance subsidiary, Tugu Pratama, with both set to take place in the first half of the year.\par \par \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  is not the only player showing a renewed interest in the domestic hydrocarbons sector, with overseas firms also getting in on the act. On Jan. 24, Japan's \uc2 Mitsubishi Corporation\uc2  announced it was entering into a joint venture with the \uc2 Korea Gas Corporation\uc2  (\uc2 Kogas\uc2 ), the world's largest buyer of natural gas, to set up Sulawesi LNG Development, which would in turn be the largest stakeholder in Donggi-Senoro LNG. Donggi-Senoro is set to develop a $2.8 billion liquid natural gas (LNG) facility in central Sulawesi in partnership with \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  and Medco LNG Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Between them Mitsubishi and \uc2 Kogas\uc2  will hold 60 percent of Donggi-Senoro LNG's shares, with the South Korean firm and Japanese clients set to take most of the plant's 2-million-ton annual output when it comes online in 2014. Feedstock for the Donggi-Senoro facility will come from the Matindok fields and Senoro-Toili field. On Jan. 31, Mitsubishi issued a statement saying it had just spent $260 million to buy a 20 percent stake in the later field from Medco, a move that positions the Japanese corporation at the core of the Donggi-Senoro operation, giving it a role in all up- and downstream activities.\par \par \uc2 The final agreement for the Donggi-Senoro plant had been delayed due to prolonged discussions between the joint venture partners and the government over the share of gas that would be made available for domestic use. Though a leading exporter of gas, Indonesia increasingly needs to meet growing local demand, with this prompting a scaling back of overseas gas sales, at least until production can be boosted. In mid-January, industry regulator BPMigas issued a statement saying that Indonesia would ship only 362 cargoes of LNG this year, down from the 427 in 2010.\par \par \uc2 The growth in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has seen domestic demand for fuel and gas rise sharply, with this increasing demand coinciding with a spike in prices, which has seen the cost of imports climb. Imports were up by 22 percent in January, with \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  bringing in 13.4 million barrels of oil products in the first month of 2011, with some categories up by 100 percent or more. Fuel oil imports rose from 170,000 barrels in December to 510,000, while the flow of overseas diesel jumped to 5.2 million barrels, up from the 2.6 million the month before.\par \par \uc2 While some of this increase was offset by falls in import levels of certain top-grade products such as jet fuel and high-octane gasoline, in part linked to the government's decision to reduce fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , overall Indonesia's oil bill is set to rise further as demand builds.\par \par \uc2 The growing need for natural gas has prompted \uc2 ExxonMobil\uc2  to unveil plans to convert the Arun LNG plant into a LNG-receiving terminal, with two units at the facility to be changed into a re-gasification plant that would be used to supply local consumers in Sumatra.\par \par \uc2 With the Arun field in Aceh set to halt exports by 2014 as \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  fall, the plant will be used to process gas from other Indonesian fields or from abroad, with the initial conversion work and a distribution pipeline set to be completed before the end of 2012.\par \par \uc2 Such moves to guarantee supplies will be welcomed by many, especially the country's industrialists, who have been voicing concerns that shortages could slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. According to Achmad Widjaya, the secretary-general of the Forum for Natural Gas Using Industries (FIPGB), the government and the state gas distributor, \uc2 Perusahaan Gas Negara\uc2  (PGN), had yet to set the exact allocation of gas for industrial purposes for 2011. Shortages and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over supply have already prompted some heavily gas-reliant industries, such as ceramic producers and cement manufacturers, to cut back on work hours, and continued shortfalls could cause foreign investors to move their operations to other countries, Achmad warned on Jan. 18.\par \par \uc2 Though Indonesia has ample gas \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , its long-time focus on exports has meant it has been slow to put in place sufficient infrastructure to process and distribute supplies to the local market.\par \par \uc2 The challenge facing Jakarta will be to step up investments needed for the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  while ensuring that enough gas is reserved for the export market, with this in turn essential for generating the revenue to fund infrastructure developments at home.\par \par \uc2 The writer is the editorial manager of Oxford Business Group.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110207e7270001h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
