\par\par \b \uc2 News Focus: GOVT TO ACCELERATE INFRASTRUCTURE DEVELOPMENT\b0\par\par\uc2 917 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 February 2011\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 Asia Pulse Pty Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.   \par \par \uc2 By Andi Abdussalam\par \par \uc2 Jakarta, Feb 22 (ANTARA) - The government will accelerate the realization of infrastructure projects worth US$90 billion as part of its efforts to integrate the country's six \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth corridors, to offset inflation and boost finished goods exports.\par \par \uc2 In essence, the government wishes to accelerate and expand \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development in which all sectors and development focuses are integrated regionally. In the future, exports will be carried out in the form of finished goods.\par \par \uc2 "We do not want to only export raw materials. Each region must have a prime product. Therefore infrastructure and manufacturing development will be done based upon regional potentials," Chief \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister Hatta Rajasa said on Monday.\par \par \uc2 He said that the funds that have been discussed several times amounted to US$90 billion to be put in infrastructure, airports, and railway and toll road development.\par \par \uc2 "That is what is meant by acceleration," the chief \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister said.\par \par \uc2 In that way, the government hopes that inflation could be offset and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth could be boosted.\par \par \uc2 If the best scenario is implemented, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could grow by 7.1 percent to 7.6 percent during the 2011 - 2014 periods. It even has the potential to reach 8 percent in accordance with expectation if infrastructure is improved.\par \par \uc2 "If the participation of the private sector in the development of infrastructure could reach 50 percent of the needed investment, and the government increase increases its \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for transportation infrastructure to 20 percent, the matter (8 percent growth) could be reached," Fauzi Ichsan, senior economist of Standard Chartered Bank, said.\par \par \uc2 He said that toll roads, electricity plants and ports were among the infrastructure facilities that needed to be improved. After all, the development of infrastructure in the last decade had run very slowly and depended on the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The government is not yet able to allocate the needed funds while the participation of the private sector is still beyond expectation," Fauzi said. Moreover, the lack of infrastructure is the main factor causing investors to be reluctant to make their investment in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Fauzi listed six points that discouraged investors, namely legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  or corruption, regional autonomy, insufficient infrastructure, labor affairs, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and import duties.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the distribution of national land transportation system remains imbalanced while the development carried out on the islands outside Java is still below their real potentials.\par \par \uc2 "Compared with those of its ASEAN neighbors, Indonesia's ports are outdated and are overloaded so that they place Indonesia in a less competitive position in the face of international trade," said Fauzi.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, land transportation infrastructure, such as roads, toll roads, railways and bridges are still concentrated in Java.\par \par \uc2 "Java is resided by 59 percent of the population and accounts for 7 percent of the country's land areas but it only contributes about 58 percent to the country's gross domestic products (GDP)," he said.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, Indonesia needs to overcome its infrastructure constraints to assure the growth of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  based on its potentials --namely to grow by about 8 percent per annum-- and to contain inflation in line with efforts to push down prices to a level equal to those in other countries in Southeast Asia.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, according to Chief \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister Hatta Rajasa, the government is planning to accelerate Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development through six \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth corridors that would integrate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development in Sumatra, Kalimantan, Java, Bali, Nusa Tenggara, Sulawesi, North Maluki, Papua and Maluku.\par \par \uc2 "There are three pillars in the corridors namely infrastructure, connectivity and human resource development and science and technology development," Hatta Rajasa said.\par \par \uc2 Regarding the implementation of the government plan, Hatta said a team would be established to monitor the implementation and problems met during the process so that they could be settled quickly and correctly. "There will be task forces assigned based on corridors in which there are also sectors," he said.\par \par \uc2 Hatta said in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  acceleration program there are eight main programs and 17 main \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities. The eight programs include industry, agriculture, mining, energy, marines, tourism, information and telecommunication and strategic zone development. The 18 activities meanwhile cover manufacturing industry involving products such as steel commodities, food and drinks and other commodities, mining that includes nickel, copper and other commodities.\par \par \uc2 In the infrastructure development, Industry Minister MS Hidayat has offered Japanese companies cooperation to develop infrastructure facilities in the country's six \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  corridors.\par \par \uc2 The minister offered the cooperation during a meeting with Japanese businessmen grouped in the Japanese chamber of commerce (Keidanren) at his office last week.\par \par \uc2 "We plan to develop infrastructures along Jabodetabek (Jakarta, Bogor, Tangerang and Bekasi), ranging from Cikarang, Karawang to Banten so that we will have complete infrastructures," he said.\par \par \uc2 He said the ministry would discuss cooperation priorities with Keidanren to develop the infrastructures. "We also promoted industrial clusters that need Japanese investment in the energy field," he said.\par \par \uc2 Earlier, Japanese business leaders grouped in the Keidanren led by its, Hiromasa Yonekura, have reaffirmed their commitment to helping the Indonesian government implement its infrastructure development program as part of the ASEAN-Indonesia connectivity system.\par \par \uc2 In a meeting with President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono who was accompanied by Hatta Rajasa last week, the Japanese business leaders expressed their commitment to the development of priority metropolitan area as one of the Indonesian development corridors.\par \par \uc2 "The President presents five areas where cooperation needs to be increased namely transportation, food sector, renewable energy development including geothermal, environment and power plants," Hatta said.\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020110302e72m0001q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
