\par\par \b \uc2 Will the  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  corridor  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\uc2  live on paper only?\b0\par\par\uc2 Rendi A. Witular, The Jakarta Post,   \par \uc2 1,438 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 10\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono launched on Feb. 22 a blueprint for the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development for the next 14 years. Inside the plan was an ambitious \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to develop \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  corridors on the archipelago's five major islands. The Jakarta Post's Rendi A. Witular looks into the issue:\par \par \uc2 Balanced regional development propelled by domestic resources was the basic idea behind the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  corridor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which was widely praised by local administration officials and businesspeople.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was included in the government's 2011-2025 acceleration and expansion \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development blueprint.\par \par \uc2 Questions, however, linger as to whether the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will actually work.\par \par \uc2 Under the scheme, the government plans to build \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  clusters and business centers on all of Indonesia's major islands to support their unique local economies.\par \par \uc2 The corridors were defined as six \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development highways, mostly located along coastlines, which would connect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth centers on five islands: Java, Sumatra, Kalimantan, Sulawesi and Papua, according to the blueprint, a copy of which was recently obtained by the Post.\par \par \uc2 For example, the northern coast of East Java would be developed as a hub for the petrochemical and shipyard industries, while the province's inland areas would be developed as centers for the food and beverage manufacturing sectors.\par \par \uc2 South Sumatra and Riau would become the nation's hubs for the oil palm processing industry under the scheme, while Bali and Lombok would be centers for the tourism industry.\par \par \uc2 Remote and isolated Papua has been slated to become a center for gas, gold and copper exploration, while its southern parts would be allocated to food plantations.\par \par \uc2 "There has never been a concept or \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has emphasized a province's unique potential like this \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  corridor [concept]," Papua Governor Barnabas Suebu said.\par \par \uc2 South Sumatra Governor Alex Noerdin had similar praise for the concept, saying the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reflected a thorough effort to detach the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development from a focus on Java.\par \par \uc2 "There will be so many things to do. The hardest part will be to convince investors to come to our area, and to set up basic infrastructure," he said.\par \par \uc2 While the government seems to have had a hard time in luring foreign investors to support such proposal, the resources of state companies will be deployed to help realize the scheme, with an expected investment of around US$90 billion slated over the next four years.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Hatta Rajasa said state companies would become the basis for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  corridor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 's success.\par \par \uc2 "We have designed the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  so that state companies will enter first in order for local businesspeople to see a real example that the plan is really being implemented well," Hatta said.\par \par \uc2 Hatta said the investment needed for the plan to work in the short-term would be provided by state companies, adding the government would allocate around 8 percent of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to develop the basic infrastructure required for the program.\par \par \uc2 State-Owned Enterprises Minister Mustafa Abubakar even required all state company executives in attendance at a recent Cabinet meeting to stand and take a vow before Yudhoyono to endorse the scheme.\par \par \uc2 State-controlled \uc2 Bank Negara Indonesia\uc2  (BNI) said it would focus most of its lending this year to finance projects planned under the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to BNI president director \uc2 Gatot Suwondo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Our lending is expected to grow as much as 20 percent this year. Most of the lending will be to sectors and projects under the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said.\par \par \uc2 The ambitious \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was based on the Industrial Road Map developed by the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) and several associations in 2007 and on input from the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee (KEN), according to KEN member Chris Kanter.\par \par \uc2 KEN, chaired by politically wired tycoon Chairul Tandjung, then forwarded the ideas to the Office of the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Businesspeople have praised the concept. We can now see an exact path for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development for the next 14 years. This has somehow boosted our confidence," said Chris, whose businesses were mostly engaged in logistics.\par \par \uc2 "But the problem with the private sector is that we will be skeptical about implementation unless there's a success story within one or two years of the implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 Chairman of the Indonesian Employers' Association (Apindo), Sofjan Wanandi, said the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was more realistic than before, and it would be Yudhoyono's hallmark legacy in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector if it could be realized.\par \par \uc2 According to Sofjan, the administration's seriousness could be measured by a meeting between Hatta, several \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers and representatives of the nation's 20 biggest conglomerates on Feb. 22 to promote the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Yudhoyono is slated to meet with local businessmen at the end of March to discuss \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  details and to find ways to prevent protracted impediments.\par \par \uc2 "The idea is good, but again more details are needed for implementation. The devil is in the details," Sofjan said.\par \par \uc2 "We need a success story from two or three state companies engaged in the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , then we will be convinced it really works."\par \par \uc2 Hatta pledged to directly handle protracted problems by closely supervising the progress of each ministry so that investors would be convinced with the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be left on paper. I'm tired of speaking merely of concepts and pledges. This time it will surely work."\par \par \uc2 Mounting doubts are understandable. Numerous ambitious projects and policies have been launched by Yudhoyono's administration. Most have run aground, leaving only a few success stories.\par \par \uc2 Protracted problems related to land procurement, bureaucratic delays, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in regulations and law enforcement, illegal fees, as well as uncoordinated central and local government policies have not been addressed thoroughly.\par \par \uc2 A set of draft laws needed for bureaucratic reform and accelerated land clearance have remained on the desks of government officials for at least three years without progress.\par \par \uc2 Less progress has also been seen on efforts to eliminate logistics bottlenecks, with the latest turmoil revolving around ferry transport between Java and Sumatra.\par \par \uc2 Cargo trucks have been trapped in lines as long as five kilometers for the last two weeks at Merak port in Banten and Bakauheni port in Lampung.\par \par \uc2 Mismanagement by state ferry company PT ASDP is blamed for the gridlock.\par \par \uc2 Poor transportation infrastructure has been widely blamed for keeping Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from growing faster.\par \par \uc2 According to the Institute of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Research (LPEM) at the University of Indonesia, the nation's logistical costs are among the highest in the world, accounting for 14.08 percent of sales revenue. In comparison, logistical costs in Japan are 4.88 percent.\par \par \uc2 The government is eying 6.4 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2011 over the 6.1 percent growth in 2010 that was propelled primarily by investments. Since 1999, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been largely fueled by domestic consumption.\par \par \uc2 Local powerhouse: Container and bulk vessels queue outside Teluk Bayur Port in Padang, West Sumatra, on Feb. 8. The West Sumatra administration and state port operator PT Pelindo II have teamed up to expand the port and boost the local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The government has required state companies to set examples of success stories in developing local economies. Antara\par \par \uc2 Overview\par \par \uc2 Sumatra Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: Ports in Metro Medan, Dumai and Palembang. A trans-Sumatra railway, power plants and mine mouths and processing plants for coal.\par \par \uc2 Target: Regional growth increases 3.4 times to US$473 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Java Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: Port expansions in Jakarta, Semarang and Surabaya, trans-Java highway and power plants.\par \par \uc2 Target: Regional growth increases 4.2 times to $1,282 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Kalimantan Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: Barito and Mahakam river ports for barge loading, railway in Central Kalimantan, toll roads linking Central and East Kalimantan\par \par \uc2 Target: Regional growth increases 2.6 times to $152 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Sulawesi Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: Irrigation network expansion, port expansion in Makassar, Bitung and Kendari, power plants for nickel processing in Southeast Sulawesi.\par \par \uc2 Target: Regional growth increases 4.4 times to $94 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Bali & Nusa Tenggara Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: Capacity expansion for Ngurah Rai International Airport, new airport international in Bali, cruise terminal in Tanah Ampo and Benoa, trans-Bali toll road, and power plants.\par \par \uc2 Target: Regional growth increases 4.3 times to $76 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Papua & Maluku Corridors\par \par \uc2 Required infrastructure: trans-Papua highway, including to Merauke, Jayapura and Merauke ports, and coal-fired power plant in Urumka.\par \par \uc2 Target: Value of regional growth increases 6.3 times to $83 billion by 2030.\par \par \uc2 Source: Office of the Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110301e73100012\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
