\par\par \b \uc2 RI among favorite investment destinations for British companies\b0\par\par\uc2 1,023 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post's Hendarsyah Tarmizi and four other Indonesian journalists were invited by the British Embassy in Jakarta recently in February to London to get firsthand information on the UK government's investment and trade \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Below is the first of two reports from the trip.\par \par \uc2 The British government recently issued a White Paper on Trade and Investment, an ambitious strategy to nurture international trade and investment through a number of actions, which, among others, include providing financial support for local firms to export and invest overseas.\par \par \uc2 Included in the strategy is a range of actions to promote market access and investment in emerging markets, particularly in Asia, which is now leading the global recovery. Its rapidly growing economies make the region a particularly rewarding destination for exports, as well as for investment.\par \par \uc2 With a large population and high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, Asia is expected to become the main engine of\par \par \uc2 the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the next decade.\par \par \uc2 The International Monetary Fund estimates Asia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow 50 percent in the next five years. A New NatWest and \uc2 Royal Bank of Scotland\uc2  study showed 65 percent of UK businesses believed Asia represented a new market opportunity.\par \par \uc2 The enthusiasm of local businesspeople about the growth potential in Asia was apparent a business seminar in London. The "Doing Business in Asia -- Meet the Experts" gathering attracted more than 200 business executives from a wide range of business activities in the country.\par \par \uc2 Similar events in Edinburgh, Newmarket and Northern Island to support the White Paper programs were also well-attended by local businesspeople.\par \par \uc2 Asia's growth potential is not only centered in China and India as many people believe. Several other countries in the region such as Indonesia and Vietnam also offer the same opportunities for global investors.\par \par \uc2 British Minister of State for Trade and Investment Lord Green acknowledged China and India were among the most promising countries to do business in thanks to their large populations, growing middle class and big\par \par \uc2 domestic markets.\par \par \uc2 But in addition to these two giants, Indonesia and Vietnam also offered the same business opportunities, he said. "In fact, the two countries are among popular export and investment destinations for UK companies," the former chairman of the \uc2 HSBC Group\uc2  told Indonesian journalists at his office recently.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia, in particular, is one of the favorite investment destinations not only for UK companies but also for other global investors. Indonesia has been identified as one of the top markets for global investors, according to a recent survey published by UK Trade and Investment.\par \par \uc2 In the survey conducted on more than 520 global executives, Indonesia was selected as the number two investment destination behind Vietnam beyond the BRICs for 2010 thanks partly to the country's relatively stable political condition, rich natural resources and large domestic market.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) said the UK was the second-largest foreign investor in the country last year after Singapore.\par \par \uc2 As one of the larger emerging markets, Indonesia has become an important investment destination. The country offers investment opportunities not only for the development of the country's rich national resources, but also for its infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government, for example, plans to develop at least 100 large infrastructure projects worth more than US$47.3 billion between 2010 and 2014. The projects, including the development of roads, ports, seaports, railways, power plants, water supply and sanitation facilities, will be offered under a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -private partnership (PPP) program. Sixteen of the PPP projects worth $32.37 billion will be offered to the private sector this year.\par \par \uc2 Green said British companies now operating in Indonesia were mostly engaged in financial services, oil and gas exploration and production activities. The London-based \uc2 HSBC\uc2 , one of the first foreign banks to operate in the country provides sharia banking services to enable it to optimally tap into the business potential in the largest Muslim-majority country.\par \par \uc2 Energy giant BP, which is headquartered in London, is also one of Indonesia's largest foreign investors. The company, which is now developing a liquefied natural gas plant in Papua, has invested $5 billion to date.\par \par \uc2 Green said that in addition to financial services and energy, the UK had much more expertise to offer ranging from advanced engineering, creative industries and transportation to environment and satellite technology to help Indonesia achieve its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth targets.\par \par \uc2 British expertise in engineering and transportation could, for example, help Indonesia improve its infrastructure problems, while sharia banking services could also help promote the use of Islamic bonds in raising funds needed for infrastructure development, he said.\par \par \uc2 Like Green, Lord Powell, the cochair of the British government's Asia Task Force, also sees the prospect of investing in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 "It doesn't take a genius to understand the business opportunity in Indonesia," he said. "Its growing middle class and high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth tell us all about its bright prospects."\par \par \uc2 Powell, who led a British trade delegation to Indonesia last year, said that with its large domestic market and relatively stable political conditions combined with its rich natural resources, Indonesia certainly offered wide opportunities to foreign investors to do business. However, he warned that no investors would come if the Indonesian government could not provide legal certainty to maintaining their long-term presence in the country.\par \par \uc2 Although the Indonesian government has amended a number of laws related to investment activities, legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains the main concern of foreign investors planning to invest in Indonesia. In fact, there remains a lot of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in many business activities in Indonesia, especially in the mining sector, such as those related to business licenses, foreign ownership and the mandatory divestment requirement imposed on foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono is aware of the problem. In his address in early January to mark the start of stock trading at the Indonesian Stock Exchange after the year-end break, Yudhoyono promised to solve the legal problems.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia certainly should make a legal breakthrough in order to be able to further promote foreign investment, if it wants to maintain its growth momentum.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110307e7370001q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
