\par\par \b \uc2 Editorial: Conflicting signals on IPO\b0\par\par\uc2 577 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Minister of State-Owned Enterprises Mustafa Abubakar and his deputy Pandu Djajanto were quoted last week by business newspapers as giving conflicting statements on planned initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings (IPO) by state enterprises. Abubakar said he would accelerate the IPO process for state companies this year to capitalize on the ongoing robust inflows of capital to the Indonesian Stock Market (IDX), citing PT Semen Baturaja, PT Angkasa Pura airport operator and PT Pelindo seaport operator as the top priorities.\par \par \uc2 Djajanto, however, said the government had decided to scale back its listing plans for state-owned companies this year from 10 to probably only one, apparently as a result of fallout from the flop of the stock market debut of national flag carrier \uc2 Garuda Indonesia\uc2  last month.\par \par \uc2 We understand global market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the wake of oil price shocks could weaken a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and the lukewarm investor response to the Garuda IPO last month may have dampened investor appetite for upcoming IPOs.\par \par \uc2 However, drastically scaling down the planned \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  listing of state enterprises is rather misguided and narrow-minded, given the multiple benefits of an IPO in light of reforming \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector businesses.\par \par \uc2 The controversies over the "high pricing" of Garuda shares and "low pricing" of state-owned \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  last November should not deter the government from floating more state companies.\par \par \uc2 These "incidents" should instead prompt the government to float more \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies on the IDX because there was, we think, excessive political intervention in the share pricing process, against the advice of the underwriters, which had led to the incorrect pricing of the two IPOs.\par \par \uc2 The objective of floating as many of the estimated 140 state companies as possible on the IDX is much broader than the state or the issuer itself simply benefiting from the IPO proceeds. It is the longer-term benefits -- promotion of good governance, better transparency and accountability through stringent disclosure requirements -- that are even more important for the reform of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector.\par \par \uc2 Yet most important is that listing on the IDX makes state companies less vulnerable to vested-interests and political intervention, which we suspect played a big part in the misguided pricings of both the Garuda and \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  IPOs.\par \par \uc2 Put another way, privatizing state companies through the IDX also means assigning the market responsibility to assess the value of these assets without political intervention. More IPOs also will increase the depth and breadth of IDX.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, empirical evidence from around the world shows that publicly-traded state companies have greater growth prospects than those under direct government management.\par \par \uc2 Abubakar immediately announced after his appointment in October 2009 a bold reform program to reduce the number of state firms to 78 by 2014 through mergers, privatization and consolidation into super-holding companies similar to \uc2 Temasek\uc2  in Singapore and Khazanah in Malaysia.\par \par \uc2 There are simply too many state companies that are often used by politicians as cash cows. In many cases the government simply does not have any business being involved in so many diverse activities that can be undertaken more efficiently by private firms.\par \par \uc2 The blunt fact is that most state companies have been grossly inefficient due in part to lax internal controls, poor accounting standards and practices and excessive exposure to arbitrary government interference.\par \par \uc2 Floating these companies on the IDX is one of the most effective ways of improving their governance and putting them beneath the necessary market oversight.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110315e73f0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
