\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Mid-East tension and Japan's disaster: The impact on RI  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 874 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Kahlil Rowter, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The direct and immediate impact of higher oil prices on account of the tension in the Middle East and the disaster in Japan is not expected to be severe. However the indirect impact on global confidence could be; Indonesia should brace itself for this.\par \par \uc2 With tension spreading in the Middle East and especially in oil-producing regions, oil prices have risen to above US$100 per barrel. And with no clear direction how the tension will be solved quickly upward pressure on oil prices will remain at least in the short-term. And now the severest disaster post-World War II has hit Japan.\par \par \uc2 The earthquake and tsunami, destructive as they were, will probably be overshadowed by the nuclear disaster in progress. Recovery in any one disaster will take sometime, let alone from a combination of them. As an oil importer as well as exporter, Indonesia is certain to feel the impact of the global oil price increase. And any significant growth slowdown in Japan as our largest trade partner will also need close attention.\par \par \uc2 The impact of an increasing oil price will be significantly felt in three areas. First is the rise in the price of unsubsidized fuel which will eventually impact inflation; second is the budgetary impact from the higher energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; and third is the trade balance.\par \par \uc2 The higher price of unsubsidized fuel, mainly for industrial use and the higher octane fuel for transportation will eventually result in higher product prices. But the pass-through is partial and not immediate. Furthermore transportation use of non-subsidized fuel is borne by households and very little will be passed on to inflation.\par \par \uc2 However, as in the previous cases, the divergence of subsidized and non-subsidized fuel prices especially when there is a plan to reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  there is incentive for misuse and stockpiling. And the incentive rises along with the difference. Hence we have seen and will continue to see fuel scarcity especially in remote regions. Eventually the government will be forced to raise subsidized fuel prices sufficiently to remove this perverse incentive.\par \par \uc2 As for the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself, with revenues coming in from oil and gas production, having to pay for higher \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will probably not have a significant negative impact. The government's own calculation is for the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to rise about Rp 17 trillion if average oil prices rise to $100 per barrel for the whole of 2011. At the same time the government has around Rp 47 trillion left over from the 2010 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Hence there is little pressure to curtail \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  or increase \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  financing through bond issuance. In short the budgetary impact of a fuel price increase is neutral.\par \par \uc2 Our oil trade balance in 2010 was negative at about $12 billion. But the overall oil and gas trade balance was mildly positive at $630 million. And the overall trade balance was about $22 billion.\par \par \uc2 The potential impact from the disaster in Japan is on our trade. Japan is our largest export market (16 percent) and also the largest import source (13 percent). The main exports to Japan are oil and gas, coal, rubber and metals. And the main imports are steel, machineries, vehicle and chemicals. Most of our exports are necessities and energy will become even more important as Japan reduces its nuclear electricity production. Hence our exports to Japan will probably not decline even in the face of its lower GDP growth.\par \par \uc2 There's even the possibility that Japan's raw material imports will rise for reconstruction. Indonesia's imports might suffer from supply problems but this should not be major or prolonged on account of: 1. We are not a major export destination from Japan; 2. Stockpiles can sustain supply in the short-run; 3. Indonesia can source from other countries.\par \par \uc2 Aside from the direct impact of oil prices and the disaster in Japan is the indirect but more perilous loss in global confidence like what took place in 2008. In that period the US underwent severe financial stress, followed by key European countries. At the core was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the distribution of bad mortgage loans and how far each financial institution could withstand the pressure. The loss of confidence was then propagated by the global interconnectedness. This time the epicenter is Japan which is the third-largest global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Going ahead, questions on the soundness of Japanese financial institutions could trigger erosion of confidence, which are similarly global in nature. And with most countries' \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  situations and financial sectors still recovering from the 2008 crisis, this could be severe. If the 2008 problem was mainly with not knowing where the bad debts were, this time the problem is not having much certainty about how severe the losses in Japan could tally up to. The key here is risk aversion.\par \par \uc2 The way it works is through equity and bond markets losing confidence in a big way. Japan is one source of cheap financing where investors borrow cheap in the Japanese market and park money with higher returns in emerging countries including Indonesia. Such a strategy is called carry trade.\par \par \uc2 The writer 