\par\par \b \uc2 World Water Day: Responding to the urban challenge\b0\par\par\uc2 888 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 23\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Nila Ardhianie , Contributor, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The United Nations General Assembly designed March 22 of each year as World Day for Water following the 1992 United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED) in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. This year's celebration of World Water Day (WWD) carries the theme "Water for Cities: Responding to the Urban Challenge". In observance of WWD 2011, The Jakarta Post is running a special report on clean water-related problems and challenges in Indonesia's urban environment. The report also discloses the participation of organizations and the private sector in helping tackle the problems related to clean water.\par \par \uc2 In 2007, a United Nations report, The 2007 Revision of World Urbanization Prospects revealed that for the first time in history more people are living in cities than in rural areas.\par \par \uc2 The report provides the official UN estimate and projections of urban, rural and city populations of all countries in the world up to 2050.\par \par \uc2 It says by the end of 2008, half of the world's 6.7 billion people will live in urban areas and population growth in urban areas will be concentrated in Asia and Africa. "Although Asia and Africa are the least urbanized areas, they account for most of the urban population of the world," said Hania Zlotnik, director of the Population Division of the Department of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Affairs (DESA), which prepared the report.\par \par \uc2 Data from the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) shows a slightly different story; only in 2015 Indonesia will have more people living in urban areas.\par \par \uc2 Until 2010 the percentage is 46 percent people living in urban areas and the remaining 54 percent still living in rural areas.\par \par \uc2 These statistics surely will form our common future. The wave of urbanization is very big and fast; far too fast for planners and policymakers who do not equip themselves with updated information and therefore cannot respond appropriately to the new data.\par \par \uc2 The 2011 World Water Day theme "Water for Cities: Responding to the Urban Challenge" aims to spotlight and inspire governments, organizations, communities, and individuals to actively engage in addressing the challenges of urban water management.\par \par \uc2 It aims to focus international attention on the impact of rapid urban population growth, industrialization and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by climate change, conflicts and natural disasters on urban water systems.\par \par \uc2 The current primary driver of urban population growth is no longer rural-urban migration but internally generated population growth within urban settlements themselves or migration between urban areas. As Indonesia is not managing urban population growth well it will likely face a rise in urban poverty.\par \par \uc2 In relation to water and sanitation issues, urbanization in Indonesia will result in huge numbers of people living without sufficient safe water and sanitation facilities in urban areas.\par \par \uc2 It will expand the areas and number of people without service from piped water supply companies and bring some serious challenges such as service delivery, sanitation, investment and social audit.\par \par \uc2 The latest National Socio \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Survey, BPS, shows only 15 percent of households using piped water as their source of drinking water and donor and government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is currently aiming to support private sector investment in water and sanitation.\par \par \uc2 But history teaches us that water and sanitation is not an attractive investment for the private sector, as illustrated by the limited new investment by private operators in water and sanitation services.\par \par \uc2 Therefore the future hinges on reforming \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  utilities, to help them operate more efficiently and effectively in order to improve their service.\par \par \uc2 The other major challenge we face in the near future is how to deal with the sanitation crisis. Growth in urban population definitely will bring with it a very huge problem related to human waste and with the current level of intervention we have now, Indonesia may need to be prepare for disease outbreaks caused by improper treatment of waste.\par \par \uc2 Swelling urban population growth also causes floods as rainfall cannot be absorbed into the soil due to the impervious land cover.\par \par \uc2 Rainfall in watersheds having vegetation can be absorbed into the soil and stored as ground water and much of the rainfall does not move into streams and canals all at once, which helps prevent flooding.\par \par \uc2 But when areas are urbanized, much of the vegetation and top soil is replaced by buildings, roads, parking lots, and pavement.\par \par \uc2 When natural land is changed, rainfall that used to be absorbed into the ground now enters the local waterways. These waterways are usually not designed to handle large amounts of water, and are prone to flooding.\par \par \uc2 The above challenges require a more robust infrastructure and a larger \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, the government should begin to allocate more of its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the water supply and sanitation sector. The 2010 National \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  only allocated 0.01 percent of its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for this sector.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is already far from sufficient to answer current