\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Delay in oil  \highlight22\uc2 subsidy \highlight\uc2  lifting = Market overhang\b0\par\par\uc2 746 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 March 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Arga Samudro, Bahana Securities, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Turmoil in the Middle East has caused reverberations in oil prices on concerns of crude supply disturbance, particularly if political coups spread to other big oil producers like Iran, Kuwait, and off course Saudi Arabia, which contribute to approximately one-fifth of the world's proven oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the second largest crude oil producer in the world behind Russia.\par \par \uc2 The global oil price has escalated to beyond US$100 a barrel on the outbreak of civil unrest in Egypt and Libya since mid-February, applying extra pressure on inflation world wide and exacerbating price pressure previously caused by bad weather. According to the World Bank, risk in global foods price index is now close to peak level seen in 2008.\par \par \uc2 Although the recent oil price spike may be temporary in nature, it is possible that the Mid East chaos could be prolonged as the Libyan civil war intensifies. Even fear of Japan's nuclear crisis had only managed to keep oil price below the $100 a barrel for a very brief period of time. Continued oil escalations would undoubtedly slow the current global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, and also be harmful for our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Historically speaking, in 2008, the government decided to cut its fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and raised subsidized fuel prices when the Indonesian Crude Oil Price (ICP) persisted well above $100 a barrel for three consecutive months, boosting energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 223 trillion or up 90.1 percent year-on-year.\par \par \uc2 It is worth noting that while Indonesia is a net exporter of crude oil, but the country is a net importer for fuel products. Therefore, since crude oil surplus has diminished while domestic fuel production and domestic consumption gap has widened (exhibit 1), every additional $1 a barrel increase in oil price would weigh on the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As shown in exhibit 2, if we take into account Bahana's estimates to adjust for macroeconomic assumptions, which have been used in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government would require Rp 10.4 trillion incremental fund to cover Rp 135 trillion in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  based on our calculation. And this is still manageable in our view.\par \par \uc2 Note that the additional \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not too high as we estimate stronger rupiah at 8,800 a dollar compared to the government's target of 9,250 a dollar. On the flip side, if the ICP were to reach $140 a barrel, the government has to bear higher \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 2.1 percent of GDP, assuming no higher subsidized fuel prices.\par \par \uc2 A bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  means that the government needs more funding as currently they have targeted to issue Rp 126.6 trillion government bonds in 2011. This would affect the domestic bond market. Given additional supply of bonds from the government and higher interest rate expectation, more foreign investors would be attracted as yield ascends this year.\par \par \uc2 Going forward, the government plans to bring down fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from 2010 level of Rp 88.9 trillion to Rp 44.3 trillion in 2014. Nevertheless, the government is still unsure whether to unveil its subsidized fuel limitation program this year or not as the program has been postponed until further notice.\par \par \uc2 The main reason for the government's decision to delay its plan to remove oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to private cars has been widening price differentials between regular gasoline (Premium) and non-subsidized fuel (Pertamax) caused by continued higher global oil prices.\par \par \uc2 This will render this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ineffective. We also believe that it would be difficult for the government to provide sufficient gas stations within the entire Java before the second half of this year, not to mention the unclear methodology in preventing black market activities from taking place in the distribution process.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, we are of the view that higher subsidized fuel prices should be implemented sooner rather than later in order to alleviate state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  inefficiencies and reallocate oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  allotment to infrastructure projects and alternative energy development which would have a much more high quality impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and its multiplier effect. However, this plan must be accompanied by sufficient social welfare bill to compensate deterioration in purchasing power as inflation spikes.\par \par \uc2 Until then, unfortunately, market players will have to live with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the lifting of oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This provides a medium-term overhang for the market as to when inflation will eventually spike.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at Bahana Securities.\par \par \uc2 ARGA\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110324e73o0001j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
