\par\par \b \uc2 The week in review : Messy country\b0\par\par\uc2 905 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 April 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 It is not surprising that business and investment in this country may not be as attractive as it should. Whether in sports organizations, government offices or the banking system, the rule of the jungle and unchecked self-profiteering seems to be the norm rather than the exception.\par \par \uc2 This week was awash with cases that should never have made headlines, but did. How will the country's sports ever excel when organizational rifts seem to dominate the news more than the actual sports events themselves?\par \par \uc2 After a protracted dispute over the leadership of the Indonesian Soccer Association (PSSI), the government decided to step in with no less than the President himself throwing his support behind the youth and sports minister's denounciation of the PSSI leadership under chairman Nurdin Halid and secretary-general Nugraha Besoes.\par \par \uc2 "I think the measures were taken by the government, KONI [National Sports Committee] and KOI [National Olympics Committee] simply to save our soccer, fulfill the people's wishes and provide a solution to the debacle," President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono said.\par \par \uc2 Youth and Sports Minister Andi Mallarangeng announced the government would no longer acknowledge the PSSI leadership under Nurdin and Nugraha following a deranged congress in Pekanbaru, Riau, last week.\par \par \uc2 Soccer, like life, is politics in action. And the actions of the government can also be interpreted as such with Nurdin often being identified as a pawn of Yudhoyono's main political rival.\par \par \uc2 Sadly, it is the sport itself that is suffering through this debacle as the competition on the political field spills over to the soccer pitch.\par \par \uc2 As if there were not enough examples of systemic graft within our ranks, the Judicial Mafia Taskforce said it had found -- surprise, surprise -- widespread corruption in the country's land management sector and urged the government to focus on reforming land management.\par \par \uc2 The taskforce said 22 percent of the 4,301 reports it received were related to the land sector.\par \par \uc2 "That indicates there is a big problem in the land management system in the country. I'd say it's time to reform \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services in the land sector because it affects the livelihoods of many citizens," Judicial Mafia Taskforce member Mas Achmad Santosa told The Jakarta Post.\par \par \uc2 The KPK's 2010 \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Sector Integrity Survey, which was conducted between April and August last year involving 12,616 respondents in 22 cities, showed that the land agency, which has local offices across the country, failed to reach the KPK's minimum standards of integrity.\par \par \uc2 As reports of corruption sprout like mushrooms, criticism has also emerged of the government's proposed amendments to the 2001 Anticorruption Law, which critics claim will reduce the legal penalties for corruption and allow some graft convicts to avoid prison.\par \par \uc2 Among the bill's controversial articles is one that would reduce the minimum custodial sentence for corruption from four years' imprisonment to one. Another article stipulates that those convicted of embezzling less than Rp 25 million (US$28,000) in state funds could avoid prison if they returned their ill-gotten booty.\par \par \uc2 Todung Mulya Lubis from Transparency International Indonesia also criticized a revision that would strip the KPK of its authority to prosecute corruption cases, which would effectively limit the KPK only to investigations.\par \par \uc2 Todung said the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  should strengthen the KPK by allowing it to hire independent investigators and prosecutors.\par \par \uc2 KPK deputy chairman M. Jasin said any revisions had to improve existing laws and not "weaken the fight against corruption".\par \par \uc2 Eva Kusuma Sundari, a legislator from the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P)and a member of the House's Commission III overseeing legal affairs, said despite flaws such as stipulations that would strip those convicted of corruption of their wealth, the law contained improvements.\par \par \uc2 As the week drew on news also broke that even banks were easily being manipulated from within as was confirmed by news that a client relation manager at Citibank was able to embezzle Rp 17 billion (US$2 million), from customer accounts.\par \par \uc2 With so much bewildering news it was somewhat incongruous to hear Yudhoyono close the week highlighting to businesspeople the achievements of his administration. He also reportedly lectured them about the requirements to work harder to ensure the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress.\par \par \uc2 The audience also had the opportunity to "enjoy" one of Yudhoyono's musical compositions, From Jakarta to Oslo for Our Earth.\par \par \uc2 The President said entrepreneurs -- who have frequently complained about the government's failure to eradicate corruption, legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , poor infrastructure and other barriers to trade -- that they should have far-reaching vision, up to the end of the 21st century.\par \par \uc2 In his address to mark the official opening of a three-day national leaders' meeting of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, the President disclosed plans to set up a new bank to finance $300 billion in investments for the next 15 years to accelerate the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. Yudhoyono said the bank could be in the form of an agriculture bank, a micro-credit bank or a micro-finance bank. He said $100 billion would be sourced from state-owned enterprises, $85 billion from the private sector and $100 billion from foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 This is not the first time the President has spoken boldly of his visions. One can only hope this is more than the average idle presidential chatter.\par \par \uc2 -- Meidyatama Suryodiningrat\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110403e7430000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
