\par\par \b \uc2 Land acquisition bill a silver bullet?\b0\par\par\uc2 Hasyim Widhiarto, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,291 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 April 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 This is the second of two reports on land acquisition fiascoes hampering the development of key \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure projects that are badly needed to help the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  expand. With no immediate measures in place, no definitive end is insight. The Jakarta Post's Hasyim Widhiarto explores the issues:\par \par \uc2 The much-awaited bill on land acquisition is widely expected to miraculously be a silver bullet that would end all hurdles impeding key infrastructure projects.\par \par \uc2 Some activists, and businesspeople, however, remain cautious over the success rate of the bill if it were realistically enforced.\par \par \uc2 The government proposed the bill in December to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , suggesting not only acceleration of infrastructure development, but also reinforcement of investor confidence by removing all \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the sector.\par \par \uc2 For example, under the bill the government would handle the acquisition of land needed for construction of, among others, infrastructure related to education, dams, irrigation, landfills, state hospitals, railways, roads and highways, before opening up a project tender.\par \par \uc2 Under the bill, the government will also assign a team of independent appraisal to value land prices. However, the price deal is subject to be finalized through negotiation between landowners and the government.\par \par \uc2 The bill also grants district courts with authority to arbitrage land acquisition disputes within 30 days. The court verdict will be considered final and cannot be appealed in a higher court.\par \par \uc2 Speaking before participants of the Indonesia International Infrastructure Conference and Exhibition 2011 earlier this month, Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Hatta Rajasa said the government had contemplated the proposed law as crucial and was upbeat to see it ratified by July this year.\par \par \uc2 "We have also seen a strong commitment from the House [to ratify the bill on time]," he said.\par \par \uc2 But skepticism remains.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Toll Road Association chairman Fatchur Rochman questioned the absence of key articles stipulating the settlement of financial disputes between banks and investors engaged in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure projects.\par \par \uc2 "I think the bill needs stipulation regarding whether it's allowed or not for banks to take over an ongoing project from investors in case the later defaulted on their loans," he said.\par \par \uc2 "It would be unfair if the government allowed banks to confiscate the project and leave the investor with nothing," he added.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry deputy chairman for infrastructure, construction and property, Zulkarnain Arief, believed the bill alone would not significantly attract private sector investment to the country's infrastructure potential unless the government provided reliable financial back-up.\par \par \uc2 "Aside from enforcing the law [after it is ratified], the government can attract more investors by urging state banks to provide \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure investors with long-term loan options and competitive \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said.\par \par \uc2 The National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) recently estimated private sector funds needed for transportation facilities alone reached Rp 51.7 trillion (US$5.8 billion) a year, with electricity infrastructure costing another Rp 41.2 trillion.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Works Ministry last year said they wanted at least 125 kilometers toll road constructed annually by 2014.\par \par \uc2 The target, however, seems to be very difficult to realize because all 24 priority toll road projects in Java, which make up a total of 949 kilometers, have been idle since 2007 due to soaring land prices and construction costs.\par \par \uc2 To ease the problem, government has thus far issued last year a presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on land acquisition that stipulated, among others, the government's role in land acquisition prior to project tender.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a revision to a previous \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  issued in 2005 and 2006, which failed to include mechanisms on land price negotiation.\par \par \uc2 Contacted separately, Toll Road Authority Agency (BPJT) chairman Achmad Gani Ghazali Akman guaranteed the bill would help expedite infrastructure development, as it would give more certainty to investors in planning their schedule for their project construction.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) legislator Daryatmo Mardianto, who leads the House's special committee deliberating the bill, said the committee was upbeat to pass the bill on schedule by this year since it had successfully run a series of hearings with non-governmental organizations (NGOs), agrarian experts. related ministries and state owned companies during the past three months.\par \par \uc2 The committee, according to Daryatmo, had also completed working visits to Aceh, Bali, North Sumatra, North Sulawesi and Papua to seek insights from both local government and community leaders.\par \par \uc2 "From the hearings and working visits, most of our sources have demanded us to elaborate several points in the bill related with basic definition of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests and land acquisition," he said.\par \par \uc2 Starting next month, the committee, according to Daryatmo, will run a series of hearing with, among others, 25 governors, the Supreme Court chief and several other state-owned companies.\par \par \uc2 "Since the law is also regulating land acquisition for security purposes, we will also invite the military and the National Police chiefs in our upcoming hearing," he said.\par \par \uc2 But Agrarian Reform Consortium (KPA) is not impressed with bill. The KPA is an NGO engaged in advocating land dispute and agrarian reform.\par \par \uc2 KPA chairman Usep Setiawan criticized the bill for scrapping the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  rights to appeal the court verdict on the land acquisition dispute, saying the rule had violated citizens' right to follow a fair legal proceeding.\par \par \uc2 "If the House insists on passing the law, the government will finally have a greater power to evict citizens, particularly the poor, under the name of development," he said, adding that the KPA was ready to file a judicial review, should the bill passed with such stipulation.\par \par \uc2 Several key articles in the bill\par \par \uc2 Article 13: Land acquired for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests are those needed for the construction of:\par \par \uc2 a. \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  roads, toll roads, tunnels, railways, railway stations and train supporting facilities.\par \par \uc2 b. Dams, irrigation, water sanitation, clean water and waste-water treatment facility and other forms of irrigations.\par \par \uc2 c. Ports, airports and bus terminals.\par \par \uc2 d. Other kinds of projects for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  purposes will be regulated by Presidential Decree.\par \par \uc2 Note: There is no clear definition of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests. The government has the authority to classify the kind of projects considered to be within the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest. Activists criticize this would legalize government actions to evict poor people.\par \par \uc2 Article 42 (3) the District Court verdict is the first and final in land acquisition dispute.\par \par \uc2 Note: The article eliminates citizens' right to appeal a verdict to a higher court.\par \par \uc2 Article 45 (2) Residents must hand over legal documents of their land before receiving payment during land acquisition procedures.\par \par \uc2 Note: Most land owners in Indonesia, especially those living in remote areas, have not obtained any land certificates due to various factors, including poverty and lack of knowledge in demanding for certificate. Such requirement would potentially harm citizens' rights to receive a fair amount of payment for their land.\par \par \uc2 Land clearance facilities\par \par \uc2 1. Land capping\par \par \uc2 The government has allocated Rp 4.89 trillion from the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to support land acquisition processes for 28 toll road projects since 2008.\par \par \uc2 The realization of the land clearance had amounted to Rp 264 billion and Rp 235 billion as of December 2009 for three toll road sections; the Bogor Ring Road, Semarang -- Surakarta, and Cinere -- Jagorawi.\par \par \uc2 The government allocated Rp 1 trillion in 2009 and Rp 1.2 trillion in 2010 for land capping.\par \par \uc2 2. Land revolving fund\par \par \uc2 The government has allocated Rp 1.44 trillion for land revolving fund that will be used to finance 23 Toll Road sections. As of 2010, Rp 800 billion has been allocated, while more than Rp 700 billion has been disbursed.\par \par \uc2 3. Land freezing\par \par \uc2 Land allocated for government-initiated projects is not allowed to be traded unless there is a permission from governor or mayor or regent.\par \par \uc2 Source: Transportation Ministry\pa