\par\par \b \uc2 Trade and poverty: Lessons for Indonesia\b0\par\par\uc2 1,428 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Hasiando G. Manik, Contributor, North Carolina, US\par \par \uc2 Openness is now seen almost universally as a key component of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  required for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and aggregate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  well-being. It is believed to have been central to the remarkable growth of industrial countries and to their successful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, the continued existence of widespread poverty represents perhaps the greatest failure of the contemporary global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the greatest challenge it faces. Are the two phenomena connected? Does trade globalization contribute to the great divergence between countries? Do some countries gain more from trade than others?\par \par \uc2 Jeffrey G. Williamson, the former chair of the Harvard Economics Department, in his book Trade and Poverty, When The Third World Fell Behind, takes the reader back to the 19th and early 20th century when the discrepancy between the West and poorer countries started.\par \par \uc2 Williamson begins his exploration by recognizing the period of 1820 - 1913 as the first globalization. He shows evidence to support his argument.\par \par \uc2 First, Europeans opened their economies by removing long standing mercantilist policies, lowering tariffs, and removing non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  barriers.\par \par \uc2 Second, there was a world transport and communication revolution which reduced the cost of trade.\par \par \uc2 Third, there was an industrial revolution in Europe. As a consequence demand soared for imports of intermediate inputs into manufacturing (cotton, wool, tin, and rubber), fuel (coal) and luxury foodstuffs (sugar, tea, coffee, meat).\par \par \uc2 Last, the world was in peace when Pax Britannica reigned, and this trade-stimulating peace would prevail for a century. All these factors created a trade boom during the first global century.\par \par \uc2 During the 1820-1913 trade booms, poor countries came to specialize in the production and export of primary products, while western countries came to specialize in the production and export of manufactured products.\par \par \uc2 Williamson claims that in the short term there had been positive effects of globalization and European industrialization on the third world. However, in the long run, there has been an asymmetric impact of globalization on growth rates; raising them in industrial Europe and not in the pre-industrial third world, thus contributing to "the great divergence".\par \par \uc2 This asymmetric impact happened, when de-industrialization, rent seeking behavior and price volatility undermined the potential gain from trade in poor periphery countries. European countries experienced faster growth than pre-Industrial third world countries during that time.\par \par \uc2 De-industrialization was the result of several factors. First, British and continental European productivity gains in manufacturing and the world transport revolution led to declining world prices of manufactures, making production in most of the poor periphery increasingly unprofitable.\par \par \uc2 Second, people were attracted to work in agriculture rather than manufacturing since agriculture promised higher rewards.\par \par \uc2 This condition was exacerbated by the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of allocating more resources and giving incentives to favor sectors that gave higher gain. However, de-industrialization did not cause the reduction of average incomes in countries of the poor periphery since they could exploit the gains from the trade boom by increasingly specializing in primary product export.\par \par \uc2 The purchasing power of the periphery increased since manufactured goods cheapened. A typical poor periphery country lost some potential gains, although it still gained from trade.\par \par \uc2 The elite, who held most of the productive land, mines, and other natural resources, gained the most. As a result, the rent-to-wage ratio soared, and income distribution became more unequal.\par \par \uc2 Rising inequality increased the political power of the oligarchy, and it was in its interest to reinforce institutions and government policies that rewarded its rent seeking, while suppressing those that might have fostered growth. This damaged the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the long run.\par \par \uc2 The last factor was primary product price volatility. Prices of primary products are more volatile than those of manufacturing products. Since trade \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was an important source of revenue, price volatility created more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the poor periphery countries. This condition was exacerbated by high dependence on one or two primary products for export.\par \par \uc2 One lesson from this book is that in general globalization has benefits for any country, regardless of its wealth. In reference to the first global century, the periphery did not suffer a fall in GDP per capita. Indeed, GDP per capita growth was almost 1 percent per annum between 1870 and 1913. "No economists neglect the gains from trade", as Williamson says.\par \par \uc2 The implementation of the ASEAN-China Free Trade Agreement (ACFTA), which will eliminate \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  barriers within ASEAN - China between 2005 and 2015, has stimulated a vigorous debate in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Those who reject the proposal argue that it will tighten competition between industries and potentially destroy domestic industries. Thus, it increases unemployment. The supporters' claim that the implementation of ACFTA will be good for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 ACFTA will directly bring people more choices with greater variety in quality and price. Competition will encourage domestic industries and local producers to be more efficient, thus lowering prices, raising wages, stimulating production in the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and indirectly increasing quality.\par \par \uc2 Finally, the expanded role of the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the increased volume of trade will cause people to more enthusiastically champion and lobby for the improvement and maintenance of proper infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 We know from \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theory and history that in general increasing trade will drive GDP performance. The implementation of the ACFTA should be accompanied by minimizing the negative impacts on those who are hurt.\par \par \uc2 How can we minimize the negative impacts? A valuable suggestion from Williamson is to give \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for industrial inputs like education, capital goods, and research & development. To subsidize education, government should provide more affordable schools, training centers and courses.\par \par \uc2 The development of education should not only focus on certain regions but should be beneficial for all Indonesians including the poor who live in isolated regions. Education inequality within Indonesia should be minimized since education will create positive externalities to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 To subsidize capital goods, the government can give \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  relief to industries that strive to increase their productivity through the purchase of new machinery. For example, firms could be permitted to depreciate new machinery in the year of purchase.\par \par \uc2 To subsidize innovation, the government can provide \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  relief to industries that focus on research and development. These inputs' \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  along with proper investment in infrastructure, information & technology will give a benefit to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 De-industrialization and rent-seeking behavior, both of which hinder \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth should be discouraged. As Williamson tells us, de-industrialization shrinks the gains from trade, for it deprives us of the gain associated with the positive externalities from industrialization. Industrialization reverses our backwardness.\par \par \uc2 However, industrialization does not mean that we have to expunge our agriculture. Rather, we should intensify the development of primary products based processing industries, where comparative advantage exists, in order to increase value.\par \par \uc2 As an illustration, how can the total value of our coconut export be less than the Philippines and India when we have more coconut production? It is because the Philippines has a wider product range, with 100 kinds of coconut products compared to Indonesia which has 30 kinds. This fact reminds us of the importance of industrialization in order to reverse our backwardness as compared to other countries.\par \par \uc2 The other factor that we should deal with is rent-seeking behavior. Rent seeking flourishes in Indonesia. From reports in the mass media, we often hear how businessman can easily avoid \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , or at least reduce them by lobbying and bribing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials. This phenomenon of rent-seeking is not only displayed by elite or upper class but also by lower class people. We can easily pay Rp 50,000 (US$5.00) to avoid legal sanctions due to driving violations. Some rent seeking creates barriers to entry with the efficiency and income-distribution costs associated with monopoly.\par \par \uc2 To return to our opening question: Does openness cause poverty? We conclude that openness is not a root cause for the existing poverty in the world. The trade boom during the first globalization benefited all countries, although asymmetrically. These asymmetric impacts were caused by some negative factors. For Indonesia, industrialization and minimizing rent seeking is crucial.\par \par \uc2 In conclusion, although, much of Williamson's story is from the 19th and early 20th centuries, there are applicable lessons for current developing countries. Moreover, this book uses powerful theoretical arguments and massive quantitative evidence, which can be followed even by non-economist readers. It is a good read for economists, historians, students, scholars, and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers.\par \par \uc2 Trade and Poverty, When the Third World Fell Behind\par \par \uc2 Author Jeffrey G. Williamson\par \par \uc2 MIT Press, Cambridge, Massachusetts 2011\par \par \uc2 301 pages\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110508e7580000i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
