\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: The risk of global oil price  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\uc2  on 2011 state  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 419 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 May 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Arga Samudro, Bahana Securities,\par \par \uc2 We conducted a meeting with Prof. Bambang Brodjonegoro, the Finance Ministry's head of \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Office (BKF) last week. The main topic was the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in global oil price \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which would impact on the 2011 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The salient points of the meeting were as follows:\par \par \uc2 On the issue of energy, part of the problem lies in the fact that the government still cannot meet its 2011 oil lifting target of 970,000 barrel of oil per day (bpd) in the first quarter of 2011 as natural lifting declined and exploration on new blocks remained far from optimal.\par \par \uc2 On the flip side, as of April 2011, subsidized fuel consumption reached 12.9 million kiloliters, exceeding the government's target of 12.3 million kiloliters for the first four months of this year. At this point, the government expects subsidized fuel consumption will surpass its target of 38.5 million kiloliters on the back of higher non-subsidized fuel prices (read: smuggling). This should eventually push the government to adjust its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in our view.\par \par \uc2 However, instead of proposing \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjustment, the government plans to maintain subsidized fuel prices, particularly given the recent drop in oil prices on concerns over slowing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Additionally, our meeting suggests that the subsidized fuel capping program would also be postponed indefinitely.\par \par \uc2 Amid fluctuations in oil prices, the steady appreciation of the rupiah has undoubtedly lightened the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden. Based on the sensitivity analysis (Chart 1) by the Indonesian BKF, every Rp 100/US$1 appreciation will increase the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus by Rp 1.7 trillion.\par \par \uc2 Having said that, if we use BKF's sensitivity analysis and apply the most recent rupiah exchange rate of Rp 8,550/$1 and oil price of $98/barrel, the effect on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would only be a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of about Rp 2.5 trillion. This is very small in our view, suggesting that the government may continue to maintain the current fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the government, over the medium term, would still like to gradually reduce the energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  starting from 2014, in order to make the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  more efficient.\par \par \uc2 Interestingly, this plan should ensure continued popularity for the Democratic Party, President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono's political party, leading up to the 2014 elections.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at PT Bahana Securities\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110519e75j0001d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
