\par\par \b \uc2 Legal  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\uc2 , unattractive  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal \highlight\uc2  term remain major problems to lure investors\b0\par\par\uc2 Hasyim Widhiarto, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,157 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 May 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 A prominent oil and gas businessman who joined a recent gathering with President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono recalled how hard it was to convince the country's top officials to revise regulations that he thought made oil and gas exploration in Indonesia no longer competitive.\par \par \uc2 During the gathering, which was attended by no more than 20 high-profile businesspeople, the President, according to the businessman, asked him what the government should do to raise investor interest in the local oil and gas industry. When the businessman asked him to consider offering a 50 percent take of oil and gas production to companies that run explorations in the eastern part of Indonesia, the President, however, expressed strong reluctance.\par \par \uc2 "You know that [such a request] is impossible," the businessman said the President said in response to his suggestion. "If I give [the oil and gas industry] too generous \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  terms, I will be accused of selling the country to foreign companies. You have to remember that there are many people like [political activist and the 1998 Reform movement icon] Amien Rais around me."\par \par \uc2 The businessman said he was not surprised with the President's answer.\par \par \uc2 "So, maybe the catalyst [to revise oil and gas regulations] is to approach people like Amien Rais first," he said, laughing.\par \par \uc2 Despite the rising energy demand in the country, Indonesia has seen its national oil industry failing to meet the government's production targets in the last decade.\par \par \uc2 Last year, the country produced 954,000 barrels of oil per day (bpd), lower than its production target of 965,000 bpd. This year, the government has set a target to produce 970,000 bpd but a recent report from upstream oil and gas regulatory body BPMigas showed that the country's oil companies so far could produce no more than 920,000 bpd.\par \par \uc2 The country's declining oil production, however, is offset slightly by increased gas production. In 2008, Indonesia produced 1.32 million barrels of oil equivalent per day (boepd) of gas and 1.41 million boepd in the following year. Last year, the production soared to 1.5 million boepd.\par \par \uc2 Although domestic gas production is predicted to increase following the ongoing development of several gas fields in the country, Indonesia is currently in dire need of finding new oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  as there have been no more discoveries of major oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  after US-based \uc2 ExxonMobil\uc2  found the Cepu\par \par \uc2 block in Central Java more than a decade ago.\par \par \uc2 However, with various legal and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , many consider Indonesia's oil and gas industry no longer competitive compared to those in other countries.\par \par \uc2 Last year, Canadian-based think thank the Fraser Institute ranked Indonesia's investment climate for oil and gas number 111 out of 133 countries and territories in its Global Petroleum Survey. The institute also identified the causes of Indonesia's poor investment climate as corruption, poor data access and that contract terms are not always honored.\par \par \uc2 Aside from those problems, many investors have also considered production sharing contracts (PSC) no longer attractive for operators.\par \par \uc2 According to the 2001 Law on Oil and Gas, oil and gas companies operate their oil and gas concessions under production sharing contracts. Normally, oil producers receive a 15 percent take of the oil production, with the remaining 85 percent going to the government.\par \par \uc2 Many investors have considered their split too low, especially deep sea areas mostly located in the\par \par \uc2 eastern part of the country. Exploration activities in the so-called frontier areas could cost them up to 10 times more than those in Java or Sumatra.\par \par \uc2 "I always believe that business opportunity [in oil and gas exploration] is still here, but it is the regulatory framework that does not support business players like us," \uc2 Hilmi Panigoro\uc2 , the president commissioner of Indonesia's largest private oil and gas firm PT \uc2 Medco Energi Internasional\uc2 , said recently in a discussion jointly held by the University of Indonesia's School of Economics and Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government.\par \par \uc2 Aside from securing exploration concessions in a number of oil and gas blocks in Indonesia, Medco is also running oil and gas exploration overseas, including in Cambodia, Libya, Oman and Tunisia.\par \par \uc2 Hilmi also urged the government to revise the current ambiguous, dispute-prone cost recovery \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  to give oil and gas companies a long-term certainty to invest in domestic explorations.\par \par \uc2 "I think the key word to attract more oil and gas investors in Indonesia is long-term legal certainty," he said.\par \par \uc2 Under production sharing contracts, oil and gas contractors can ask for a refund for their operating costs only after they have reached the production stage. During the exploration stage, investors are also required to pay various \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including those imposed on the import of heavy equipment, a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  which is uncommon in the oil and gas industry world.\par \par \uc2 National Energy Council member Widjajono Partowidagdo supported Hilmi's view, saying that the government must start offering more\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives to investors in order to boost domestic oil and gas production.\par \par \uc2 Instead of imposing a fixed \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  term, Widjajono said it would be better for the government to apply flexible \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  terms for the oil and gas industry, allowing them to collect higher takes only when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation was good.\par \par \uc2 "Malaysia and many other countries that have applied the flexible \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  term have seen their oil production increasing, so why don't we use such an approach domestically?" he said.\par \par \uc2 The relationship between the government and investors, according to Widjajono, should be\par \par \uc2 treated like that between "husband and wife".\par \par \uc2 "If the husband or wife is getting too greedy, the other will certainly leave," he said.\par \par \uc2 The national demand for oil is estimated to stand at around 1.3 million bpd.\par \par \uc2 In order to achieve and sustain a production target of 1 million bpd, Indonesia needs to drill more than 100 wildcat wells annually, or twice the current total.\par \par \uc2 Earlier this week, BP Migas reported that 77, or 72 percent, of 107 oil and gas blocks signing contracts between 2002 and 2008 have yet to fulfill the exact commitment to conduct exploration due to various problems, including contractors' internal problems, problems with land acquisition, the absence of supporting equipment and services and the absence of data.\par \par \uc2 According to existing regulations, contractors have a total of six years to meet their contract commitments.\par \par \uc2 "If during the period of six years they do nothing their contracts will be severed," BP Migas spokesperson Gde Pradnyana said.\par \par \uc2 A 2006 Presidential Decree on National Energy \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stipulates that by 2025, the contribution of new renewable energy resources -- geothermal steam, biofuel, liquified coal, hydropower, nuclear, wind and biomass -- should make up 17 percent of the total primary energy utilization. Oil utilization is expected to drop to 30 percent, and gas and coal to increase to 30 percent and 33 percent, respectively.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110521e75l0001d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
