\par\par \b \uc2 Lessons about infrastructure development\b0\par\par\uc2 922 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 June 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Risti Permani, Adelaide, Australia\par \par \uc2 More than 500 leaders from governments, business, the media, civil society and the academic sector engaged in various sessions to address some of the most pressing issues the world is now dealing with during the World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Forum (WEF) on East Asia in Jakarta recently.\par \par \uc2 With the theme "Responding to the New Globalism", the forum promoted a new idea of globalism that has moved beyond trade. It is also about political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , industrial, environmental and social agendas in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The choice of Indonesia as the host country should be understood as a good indication of the significance of Indonesia's role in the world forum. As a member of the G20 and the chair of ASEAN, Indonesia has demonstrated its regional influence.\par \par \uc2 The WEF also built up the country's confidence through its reference to progress in Indonesia's rank in the Global Competitiveness Index (GCI). The country now ranks 44th among 139 economies.\par \par \uc2 What can Indonesia, as a WEF host country, learn from the WEF on East Asia?\par \par \uc2 One important lesson is how Indonesia should deal with the lack of infrastructure. The GCI suggests that infrastructure is among the most obvious shortcomings in Indonesia. Indonesia is dealing with a wide range of issues that lead to low investments in infrastructure development. These issues include monopoly practices in various sectors that may lead to inefficiency, for example the management of ports by the Indonesian Port Corporation, the supply of electricity by state power producer PT PLN and the railway sector by state railway firm PT KAI.\par \par \uc2 A huge expanse like Indonesia, which covers nearly two million square kilometers and consists of five main islands and about 30 small archipelagoes, with 17,508 islands and a population of over 234 million people, obviously faces a mammoth challenge that the government must settle to ensure equity in infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 Inequality in access to infrastructure and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services is not only experienced by rural communities, but also those who live in urban areas. For example, with regard to water services, there are 85 million people living in the service areas of water utilities, but only 35 percent of them are served.\par \par \uc2 Decentralisation reform put more pressure on infrastructure development in Indonesia. Under the law, all \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  service delivery functions except for defense, foreign affairs, monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, trade affairs and the legal system have been delegated to local governments since the launch of regional autonomy in 1999. Hence, decentralization poses daunting challenges for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination.\par \par \uc2 A view of India's experience with infrastructure development presented by \uc2 Ajit Gulabchand\uc2 , chairman and managing director of the \uc2 Hindustan Construction Company\uc2 , at the WEF on East Asia provided some interesting lessons for Indonesia. He said, "India is a mixed story. There are grand successes, but also utter failures."\par \par \uc2 One of the main problems that India is facing is the work allocation between local and central governments. In India, the central and state governments are very strong, while city and other local governments do not have enough authority and autonomy - and they are the ones that implement infrastructure projects.\par \par \uc2 In a similar vein, Indonesia still has high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as to which level of government is responsible for the provision of various services despite a number of regulations to clarify the matter. In addition, local governments' lack of capacity to generate income makes them highly dependent on the central government's transfers, indicating that decentralization does not necessarily improve equality in access to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services.\par \par \uc2 An important lesson from \uc2 Ajit Gulabchand\uc2  was the success of a national authority body based on a new model of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -private partnerships in India to develop infrastructure. Before the partnership was established, India could only build 11 kilometers of road per year. After it was established, India could build 11 kilometers of road per day!\par \par \uc2 Dominic Barton\uc2 , the worldwide managing director of \uc2 McKinsey & Company\uc2  and a co-chair of the WEF on East Asia, added to the list of concerns of developing countries regarding the causes of infrastructure bottlenecks.\par \par \uc2 The list includes regulatory complexity especially in regard to land acquisition, difficulties that governments of developing countries face to determine their priorities given the complexity of problems they're dealing with and regulatory certainty. He said that there has not been any country that can provide the best example to respond to infrastructure bottleneck issues.\par \par \uc2 However, Columbia and Chile provide a good example in terms of how governments invite the participation of various stakeholders to plan a collective action working with the private sector to respond to the issues. Again, this highlights the importance of communication with various stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 It is worth noting that infrastructure alone is not a sufficient condition for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. It is the complementarity between infrastructure development and other factors such as human capital that significantly affects the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 A 2011 article by Yamuchi et. al published in World Development suggests that education and local road quality are complementary, mutually increasing non-agricultural labor supply and income in remote areas.\par \par \uc2 Given relatively low investments in infrastructure by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, Indonesia should further its partnerships with foreign investors. Lack of infrastructure in Indonesia obviously provides unique market opportunities for foreign investors especially given that there are no significant barriers to trade and investment in the transport and infrastructure sectors.\par \par \uc2 At the moment, inputs for the infrastructure sector in Indonesia are dominated by domestic supplies and imports from China.\par \par \uc2 At times, solving local issues requires a global perspective.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110620e76k0000p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
