\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: The rise of emerging market brands (Part 1)\b0\par\par\uc2 1,004 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 June 2011\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 16\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2011 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Amol Titus, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 A recent trip from Jakarta to Bangalore, two cities gaining increasing international visibility, was instructive in assessing the rise of emerging market brands.\par \par \uc2 The journey to Soekarno-Hatta International Airport in a comfortable Blue Bird taxi was followed by a snack combo of local favorites J.Co donuts, Sosro bottled tea and 'kacang' Orang Tua.\par \par \uc2 The game changing Air Asia \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  airline flew me with customary efficiency to Singapore where the connecting airline, the stylish \uc2 Kingfisher Airlines\uc2 , demonstrated how to compete with the best in its class.\par \par \uc2 Bangalore, India's Silicon Valley, flashes iconic names like Tata, \uc2 Infosys\uc2  and Reliance almost immediately on arrival. And the smooth switchover from \uc2 Indosat\uc2  to Airtel ensured business connectivity.\par \par \uc2 A working lunch at The Oberoi, a torchbearer in the hospitality industry, was followed by currency exchange at the ubiquitous and aggressive Asian banking tiger, ICICI Bank. If you want to bring back\par \par \uc2 tasty kripiks from India try the Haldirams brand which more than holds its own against the Western snack majors. And yes just to keep the fiery subcontinent spices under control don't forget to consume Amul yogurt, a household name across South Asia.\par \par \uc2 There you have it -- 15 power brands mentioned and their products and services consumed just like millions do on a daily basis in their focus markets. These are all homegrown brands that after decades of battling effectively against powerful competitors from developed countries are now dominating their sectors and holding steadfast onto the consumer mindshare.\par \par \uc2 And I was pleasantly surprised to see my little experiment in emerging markets branding validated by a survey released by TLG a few days ago that showed that seven out of the top 10 brands in India belong to indigenous firms.\par \par \uc2 Many examples of indigenous local power brands abound in key emerging markets -- Haier and Huawei from China, Grameen from Bangladesh, Jollibee from Philippines, Natura in Brazil, Dilmah in Sri Lanka, Vestel in Turkey and several others.\par \par \uc2 So what explains this commendable rise in emerging markets brands and what should aspiring firms do to emulate the success of some of the aforementioned companies.\par \par \uc2 First, believe that it can be done. Of all the brands mentioned thus far J.Co probably epitomizes this best as a local variant that took on and bested the venerable Krispy Kreme in a donut-loving prime demographic market.\par \par \uc2 It is not about how iconic the developed country brand is or how big their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  power is. Yes there are several 'Goliaths' out there with their retinue of support teams -- researchers, media planners, advertisers, strategists etc -- but the unshakeable opportunity the 'David' or aspiring SME entrepreneur has relates to the willingness of ordinary emerging markets consumers to give new products a try. So if you feel you have a winning product or service proposition do not hold back.\par \par \uc2 Second, in the modern era of dwindling attention spans and information deluge, the established brands are like aging boxers. They have fought and won several rounds but must keep going on.\par \par \uc2 Switching customer loyalties keeps them on the ropes and at times rigid bureaucracies and an underestimation of the sophistication of tastes and demands in emerging markets can prove their undoing. Big MNC brands have built an industry around themselves which at times prevents them from feeling the right consumer segment pulse. Ego and arrogance can also prove to be their undoing.\par \par \uc2 Just because a brand resonated in the US, Western Europe or Japan does not mean that it will automatically appeal to consumers in emerging markets. It took Kelloggs over 15 years to understand that in India and even after decades of trying General Motors remains a peripheral automotive brand in Indonesia. Whatever the iconic status of a brand may be, its value needs to be re-emphasized anew in each emerging market. Here usage of local culture, language, symbols, festivals, consumption habits and social mores play a paramount role and local companies are able to tap into these with greater ease and flexibility than some HQ constrained MNCs.\par \par \uc2 Third, emerging markets brands often live and die by their performance in their prime home market. Thus, for Grameen the imperative of making microfinance a success in Bangladesh will spur it to increased business model innovation, risk taking, competitive pricing and cultivation of trust. For global rivals the extent of their effort will be related to the returns they expect from Bangladesh. The fallacy of expecting a "third world risk premium" wrongly creeps in at times and brand investment stalls during \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Local entrepreneurs have been quick to spot this lag effect especially when emerging markets experience difficulties.\par \par \uc2 Thus while international dairy majors might sit on the sidelines worrying about the prospects of the Vietnamese \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  going through a difficult patch at the moment, \uc2 Vinamilk\uc2  is ensuring it is consolidating its top of mind awareness among local customers.\par \par \uc2 Long term brand investment is the fourth lesson that needs to be imbibed. Tata and \uc2 State Bank of India\uc2  are brands synonymous with trust for millions of Indian consumers and this positioning of trust takes decades of painstaking effort.\par \par \uc2 In their bid to please short term oriented stock analysts some MNCs have ended up confusing their brand strategies that oscillate between multiple brands under one CEO to swift downsizing and cancellation of brands under another.\par \par \uc2 Differentiation as seen on the marketing drawing board is one thing but differentiation created in the mind of a choosy customer base is quite another. Just as they get quickly bored with their music lists, consumers look for that edge in their products to keep them interested. And because they have become masters in creating that edge that stands out from among the clutter, emerging markets brands are on an undisputable upswing.\par \par \uc2 The columnist is CEO of international strategic consulting firm, IndonesiaWISE and senior visiting faculty at School of Business Management, ITB. In the next part of this article he will provide further insights into the rise of emerging market brands.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020110625e76p0001l\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 (economic or economy) and (uncertain or uncertainty or uncertainties) and (policy or public or tax or taxation or taxes or taxed or spending or expenditure or fiscal or stimulus or budget or deficit or national debt or tariff or subsidies or subsidy or Bank Indonesia or central bank or reserves or interest rates or fiscal or legislation or legislative or house of representatives or regulation)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\br